<HEAD>HUD Audit: Island Park Officials Excluded Blacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials of <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, home village of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, rigged the distribution of federally subsidized homes in the early 1980s to keep out blacks, according to a published report. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> in its Thursday editions reported that an audit by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> indicates that one person who received preferential treatment was <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>'s cousin, <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciccimarro </PERSON> At the time, <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> was supervisor of the Town of <LOCATION> Hempstead </LOCATION>, of which Island Park is an incorporated subdivision. He was elected to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> shortly after that, the newspaper said. <PERSON> Ciccimarro </PERSON> was selected to buy a $ 40,000 <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> house, the Times said. Also receiving preferential treatment was <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> McGann </PERSON>, a village board member and a high-ranking <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> administrator whose son received a $ 44,500 house, it said. In the 1980s, <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> got enough money to build 285 houses for lower-income families. Island Park, which is 97 percent white, got enough money to build 44 homes ranging from $ 40,000 to $ 64,000. The audit does not say if the people selected for the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> houses actually were eligible to buy them. Buyers included the niece of the village clerk, the niece of a village trustee, two village supervisors, a lawyer who soon will become a village justice and the daughter of a village employee, the newspaper said. None of them are black. The <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> houses were supposed to be advertised in local newspapers so lower-income residents, especially minorities, would have a chance to buy a home. Instead, some selected residents were told in advance when the ads would appear and they slipped their applications under the Village Hall door before dawn, the Times reported. The 1984 audit recommended disciplinary action against Mrs. <PERSON> McGann </PERSON> and the village but no penalties. Mrs. <PERSON> McGann </PERSON> last year was promoted to regional <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> administrator after her friend, <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, lobbied <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the White House on her behalf, the newspaper said. When the Times requested a copy of the audit, Mrs. <PERSON> McGann </PERSON> deleted the names of eight villagers, including her son. `` This program was a mockery,'' said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Pless </PERSON>, who did the audit. `` It took everyone's tax money and gave it to the people who did n't need it.''
</TEXT>
