<HEAD>United Adds At Least One Beijing Flight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with 2nd flight offered; picks
up 6th graf pvs: `Earlier Wednesday ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, the only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carrier serving <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, announced Wednesday it was adding at least two extra flights to the three scheduled weekly to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s capital, and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> said it will join the evacuation with charter flights. `` <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> stands ready to assist Americans who desire safe and efficient transportation out of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' Chairman <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> said. The first of the additional flights from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> arrived in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on Wednesday, said spokesman <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON>. It was scheduled to to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> before returning to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, but <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON> could n't say how many of the 400 seats were occupied. United has agreed to provide the planes and crews and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will determine who boards the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747s, <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON> said. The second charter flight, a round-trip flight between <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> only, received approval from both governments late Wednesday and is scheduled to arrive Thursday, <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON> said. Two <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> commercial flights which had already made round trips between <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> earlier this week were not fully booked out of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, he noted. There were 307 passengers on one and 335 on the other, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747-100s used on the route can carry more than 400 passengers. Earlier Wednesday, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration urged all Americans to leave <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> after rifle fire broke windows at apartment buildings occupied by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government workers. While the administration noted there had been no direct threats against foreigners, it cited an increasingly chaotic situation. On Tuesday, the government's advice had focused solely on <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. United personnel reported no problems at or en route to the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> airport, <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> announced in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> that it would provide a DC-10 for U.S.-chartered shuttle flights between <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, perhaps through the weekend. The aircraft, with a capacity for 284 passengers, will operate two daily shuttle flights on Friday, airline spokesman <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. There was no immediate word from <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> about whether it would supplement it twice-weekly flight to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>.
