<HEAD>Appeals Court Restores Timber Injunction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court Wednesday restored the injunction prohibiting the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> from selling old-growth timber around northern spotted owl nests in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. Acting on an appeal brought by the <ORGANIZATION> Portland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and other environmental groups, the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> without comment restored the year-old injunction lifted last month by a federal judge. The action was praised by environmentalists, who contend the spotted owl will become extinct unless the ancient forests where it lives and hunts are preserved. The timber industry contends that thousands of jobs will be lost unless logging of old growth timber on federal lands is allowed to continue. The action means as much as 400 million board feet of timber, a third of the agency's annual harvest in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, wo n't be offered for sale, said <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Smurthwaite </PERSON>. Five timber sales on the <LOCATION> Medford </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Coos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION> districts which were sold during the course of the legal wrangling were n't included in the injunction. The action was separate from a lawsuit filed by environmentalists against the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> pending in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> that stopped harvest of 1 billion board feet of timber on national forests in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. In lifting the injunction, Judge <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Frye </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION> failed to consider new information in preparing its managment plans for spotted owls, which the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish & amp; <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has proposed for listing as a threatened species.
