<HEAD>New Seattle Bureau Chief Named</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> operations in <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> since 1985, has been appointed bureau chief in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boccardi </PERSON>, president and general manager of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, announced the appointment Wednesday. Day, 32, will take over the news cooperative's operations in four <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> offices _ <LOCATION> Olympia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yakima </LOCATION> and the control bureau in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. He succeeds <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Slaughter </PERSON>, who has been promoted to general executive at <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> headquarters. A <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> native, Day graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Holy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Worcester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, and received a master's degree in journalism from <ORGANIZATION> Marquette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>. He worked for the <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, before joining the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> in 1981. In 1982, Day was appointed <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> broadcast editor and in 1983 was promoted to news editor in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb </LOCATION>. Two years later, he was elevated to correspondent in charge of <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>. In 1988, <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> was upgraded from an office reporting to <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, to an independent bureau and Day became bureau chief.
