<HEAD>Tieless Teacher Wins Court Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A teacher was illegally suspended by a school board for refusing to wear a tie in his classroom, a circuit judge ruled Wednesday. The ruling does n't ensure that <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>, 46, will return to his <ORGANIZATION> Point </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pleasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> classroom, but it undermines the <ORGANIZATION> Mason </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>'s main charges in the math teacher's firing `` If they could n't suspend him, they sure as hell could n't fire him,'' the teacher's wife, <PERSON> Julie </PERSON>, said in a telephone from the couple's <LOCATION> Gallipolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, home. Her husband was en route to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to appear on `` The Oprah Winfrey Show,'' which planned a program Thursday on people fired because of the way they dress. The <ORGANIZATION> Mason </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> board suspended <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> three times last fall, accusing him of insubordination for violating a dress code requiring male teachers to wear dress pants and ties. <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>, whose standard classroom wardrobe consisted of blue jeans and cotton shirts, openly challenged Superintendent <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>' order, drawing suspensions lasting 4, 11 and 30 days before being fired Dec. 19. Kanawha Circuit Judge <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s ruling set aside the 11-day suspension, meaning <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> will be paid for that time, said the teacher's attorney, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kopleman </PERSON>. A hearing on the firing and the 30-day suspension is pending, <PERSON> Kopleman </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> did n't challenge the four-day suspension because he was paid. King said the dress code was improperly established and that <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> had the right to disobey rules he believed were illegal. `` If you challenge a rule that is in effect unlawful, it's not insubordination,'' said <PERSON> Kopleman </PERSON>. The board claimed <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> should have worn a tie while challenging Chambers' order. `` The superintendent did n't have the authority to unilaterally issue a dress code,'' said <PERSON> Kopleman </PERSON>. `` Only the board has the authority. That was one of our premier arguments.'' Board member <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Siders </PERSON>, who introduced a proposal to fine <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>, said Wednesday night he was n't aware of King's decision and that the board had not talked about what to do if <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>'s appeals were successful. Board president <PERSON> Emma </PERSON> <PERSON> Kearns </PERSON> could not be reached. Chambers and board attorney <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> have unlisted numbers. The next board meeting is scheduled for June 19. The controversy began in August 1988, when the board said male instructors would have to wear ties, a change from contracts teachers signed last spring. <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>, who has worked for the <LOCATION> Mason </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> school system for 19 years and is also a farmer, has spent his spare time working around the house and at a body shop he runs. Mrs. <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said her husband will be wearing denim from top to bottom on the <PERSON> Oprah </PERSON> <PERSON> Winfrey </PERSON> program Thursday. `` I pressed them before he left,'' she said. `` I seldom press them, but this is big time.''
</TEXT>
