<HEAD>GOP Official Resigns in Uproar Over Foley Memo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 6-7: ``The president,'' with Sununu interview</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A national <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> official resigned Wednesday in the uproar over a memo he wrote comparing <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s voting record with that of a homosexual congressman. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as described as `` disgusted by this entire incident'' and as considering it closed. However, <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said the resignation of `` one staffer'' was n't good enough and suggested his <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> counterpart, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s former campaign manager <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>, should be fired by the president. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON>, a press assistant in <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s 1988 presidential campaign, wrote the memo and had it distributed as communications director of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The memo, which <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON> said was sent out without his boss <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>'s knowledge, compared <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s voting record to that of liberal Rep. <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, D-Mass. The memo was titled: `` <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>: Out of the Liberal Closet.'' `` The president was very upset,'' said White House chief of staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> in an interview reported in Thursday editions of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. `` I was upset. It went too far. It was wrong. The innuendo was wrong. It's wrong not because it damages our relationship with the Democrats. It's wrong because it's wrong. `` It's a terrible thing to happen at this time. It was not appropriate or fair,'' said <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, who said both he and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had rebuked <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>, his 1988 campaign manager, Wednesday morning, shortly before the resignation was announced. <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> had telephoned <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> to apologize Tuesday night. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s spokesman said, `` He was disgusted by this entire incident.'' `` We consider the matter closed,'' he added. <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, likewise, commenting after a previously scheduled meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at the White House, said, `` The issue is closed.'' He said there was no mention of it during the meeting. Earlier at the Capitol, <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> said that on the telephone <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> had been `` deeply apologetic for any inferences of personal character.'' `` He repudiated the statement and apologized ... I accepted that,'' said <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, adding that <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> promised there would be no more such attacks. <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, in his first full day as <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> speaker, said any suggestion that he is homosexual is `` entirely untrue of course.'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commitee </ORGANIZATION>, said of <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON>'s resignation, `` One staffer ca n't take the fall for an entire <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> political operation that's up to its knees in sewer-style politics. I think it's fair to ask President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> if he'll also have his hand-picked party chairman, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>, to resign. `` 