 A senior <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official says <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s food inflation may be contributing to much of the bloody turmoil that has centered on <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON>, acting assistant secretary for economics, said the big purchase of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat announced on Monday _ a total of 1.85 million metric tons _ helped reflect `` a sensitivity within <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to this issue -LRB- of access to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat -RRB- and the need for food.'' <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON>, in an interview aired today by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> radio, said the big wheat purchase at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market prices _ even when <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> still qualified for grain under the department's price subsidy program _ was `` some indication of their need for additional grain'' during the current turmoil. `` Internally, they've had substantial increases in food prices,'' <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON> said. `` I have had one Chinese specialist tell me that food prices have gone up 30 to 40 percent in the major cities over the last 18 months.'' <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON> speculated that this rise in food prices has helped fan popular support of the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> protesters.
