<HEAD>Drought Relief Decision May Not Come Til Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If winter wheat farmers are to get any drought relief aid, it may not be decided until the end of the fiscal year, Sept. 30. During an informal meeting Wednesday with <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., said he did n't want to pass legislation that would have to be revised later `` It seems too early to cover spring planted crops,'' said <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> during the meeting which attracted 20 other senators. `` We do n't known whether such crops are going to be weather damaged. To act now on spring-planted crops shifts the risk of production almost totally to the federal government _ I do n't think that is a good idea.'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> was critical of a bill passed last month by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, calling it a `` Christmas tree'' because it promises relief to many crops other than winter wheat, just in case weather later in the year damages them. `` If we do develop legislative response, it ought to be very narrowly defined and circumscribed to the people who have been hurt,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> pointed out that rain has been falling steadily in the past few weeks, even to the point of causing planting delays in some parts of the country. <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>'s committee has not yet acted on any legislation, though a bill authored by Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan. and one sponsored by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerrey </PERSON>, D-Neb have been introduced. Those measures would extend assistance provided under the 1988 drought relief act to crops planted in 1988 for harvest in 1989 _ mostly winter wheat. But <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> said, `` If you have a winter wheat bill, it becomes the vehicle for the year,'' and he does n't want a measure the country ca n't afford. He said cost estimates for any bill are suspect at this early date, though damage to winter wheat has been estimated to be about $ 1 billion. He said he did n't want to give farmers assistance in a bill that would have to be taken away because of budget restraints. But <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said he did n't see any reason to wait. `` I hope we do n't have to hold the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> hostage until we see if there are problems in other states,'' he said. He said his bill is budget neutral, in that it would use deficiency payments being saved because of higher wheat prices to pay the farmers who are facing losses.
