<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Newt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, who rose to prominence in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> with his ethics crusades against Democrats, says he wo n't challenge a fellow <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION>'s right to vote in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> while appealing his conviction for having sex with a teen-age girl. <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> whip, said in an interview Wednesday that Rep. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> `` Buz'' <ORGANIZATION> Lukens </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> R-Ohio </LOCATION>, should not have to give up his right to vote because his conviction involved a misdemeanor, not a felony. He said the conviction for contributing to the delinquency and unruliness of a minor is `` a serious offense, but it's a serious misdemeanor'' which will not cause <ORGANIZATION> Lukens </ORGANIZATION> to lose any citizenship rights. <ORGANIZATION> Lukens </ORGANIZATION> faces up to six months in prison and a $ 1,000 fine for his conviction. `` I think the Lukens case will go to the ethics committee and I think the Republican Conference will insist on it,'' <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said. `` But I think it is inappropriate for us to impose our judgment on the courts of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'' and bar <ORGANIZATION> Lukens </ORGANIZATION> from voting while his conviction is on appeal. <ORGANIZATION> Lukens </ORGANIZATION>' chief of staff, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarrell </PERSON>, said the congressman would have no response to <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON>'s comments. `` Congressman Lukens is not going to take out time and react to every statement that comes down the pike,'' he said. `` He's taking care of business here on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> has insisted since his freshman term in 1980 that any congressman convicted of a felony should not be permitted to vote in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> while appealing his conviction. He moved to expel then-Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Diggs </PERSON>, D-Mich., in 1980 after he continued to vote following his fraud conviction, and he threatened similar action against then-Rep. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, after his 1987 conviction for accepting <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> stopped voting after the threat. `` The principle in regard to the felony convictions of <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Diggs </PERSON> was that if you're convicted of a felony, you lose certain of your political rights, including the right to vote,'' <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> said his decision not to challenge <ORGANIZATION> Lukens </ORGANIZATION>' right to vote was not influenced by his frienship with the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> congressman, who was one of the conservative Republicans who joined with <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> to form the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> in the early 1980s. He compared <ORGANIZATION> Lukens </ORGANIZATION>' case to that of Rep. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Studds </PERSON>, D-Mass., who along with then-Rep. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Crane </PERSON>, R-Ill., was censured by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in 1983 for sexual misconduct with <PERSON> Studds </PERSON> has remained in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and is now chairman of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee. <PERSON> Gingrich </PERSON> predicted that <ORGANIZATION> Lukens </ORGANIZATION> eventually will be punished by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, and he suggested that a resolution of censure, such as that imposed on <PERSON> Studds </PERSON> and <PERSON> Crane </PERSON>, might be appropriate. During the 19