<FIRST>r w PM-MedicareSurcharge     06-08 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medicare Surcharge,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel to Review Medicare's Catastrophic Health Provisions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, after narrowly rejecting an attempt to postpone major parts of the new catastrophic health provisions of <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>, has ordered a committee review of the program. The aim of the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> review is to consider reducing the income tax surcharge on the elderly that pays for the new benefits. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>, R-Ariz., fell two votes short Wednesday evening of attaching an amendment to separate legislation that would have forced a delay of at least one year in the so-called `` supplemental premium'' imposed this year on Medicare-eligible individuals to pay for a package of benefits that start taking effect next January However, <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> also would have pushed back those benefits yet another year, and opponents argued that his proposal effectively would have killed major parts of the program approved overwhelming by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last summer. It is the first major expansion of Medicare since its creation two decades ago. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, seeking to head off the <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> attempt, introduced a substitute amendment that put the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on record as instructing the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to look into reducing the surtax if it is shown that more money is being collected than will be needed. <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, first raised that possibility several weeks ago but the administration, as well as influential <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leaders, are on record against any tax rollback. In debate on <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>'s proposal, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> also pledged to look closely at ways to exempt from the catastrophic surtax those retired Americans who have equal coverage under `` Medigap'' policies that are paid in full or part by their former employers. And he said he would renew efforts to attach the catastrophic coverage to Part B of Medicare, thus making it voluntary. Part B of Medicare, the section that pays doctor bills, is voluntarily taken by more than 95 percent of those eligible _ in large part because the federal government foots the bill for 75 percent of the costs. Although members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have been hit by thousands of letters protesting the new catastrophic program, opponents of the <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> proposal argued that opponents still represent a tiny minority of the 32 million people covered by <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>. The idea behind the financing mechanism adopted last year was that _ with huge budget deficits making it impossible to provide new government benefits without additional revenue to pay for them _ it was reasonable to expect that those being offered additional benefits be required to pay for them. Moreover, framers of the program maintained, it was fair for middle - and upper-income retired Americans to pay a proportionately larger share of the cost just as the federal tax system in general is pegged to a percentage of income The catastrophic 15 percent tax surcharge follows that principle, except the maximum imposed on any individual this year is $ 800, regardless of income. Opponents of the <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> attempt argued that an estimated 59 percent of the 32 million Medicare beneficaries do not have enough income to qualify for income tax and would pay only $ 4 a month for the additional coverage. They cited <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> estimates that 70 percent of those eligible for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> would pay $ 100 or less a year in additional surtaxes and that only 5.6 percent in upper income levels would pay the maximum $ 800 tax. The catastrophic coverage started taking effect Jan. 1 with unlimited hospitalization coverage after a once-a-year $ 560 deductible. However, a $ 1,370 cap on out-of-pocket doctor bills does not kick in until next year and a new prescription drug benefit begins a three-year phase-in period in 1991. It was those benefits beginning next January that <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> wanted to delay, along with the surtax imposed to finance them. Prior to Jan. 1, <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> provided full hospital coverage for only 59 days a year. <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> pays 80 percent of physician bills after a $ 75 annual deductible, but until the new catastrophic provisions on doctor fees take effect there is no cap on the patient's share.
