<HEAD>Navy Seeks End to Contractor's Favored Status on Cruise-Missile Engines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, faced with a declining need for cruise-missile engines because of arms-reduction treaties, wants to torpedo a 1978 agreement that requires it to buy 240 of the components annually from a <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> company. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s determination to end <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>'s favored position in supplying the engines has prompted intervention by Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Democrat who for years has criticized the Pentagon for waste and non-competitive procurement practices. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> asserts the agreement with <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> is illegal under a 1984 law authored by <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> oversight of government management subcommittee. <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> on Wednesday accused the Pentagon of trying to break a promise out of convenience rather than a concern for the law. `` I think it is pure expediency, and it is full out unfair,'' <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said. The outlines of the agreement were contained in correspondence between <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> made public both by the senator and a Washington-based whistle-blower group, the Project on Military Procurement. The agreement, negotiated because the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> wanted a second source of F107 engines for the Tomahawk cruise missile, required <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Walled </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, to license its technology to a competitor, <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In return, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> agreed to buy at least 240 engines a year from <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION>, plus 25 percent of any additional purchases up to 1,200 engines annually. The agreement has no expiration date and applies to all government contracts for F107 engines. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> must contract through <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> in buying engines from <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> has been paid about $ 36,000 for each of the 708 engines built by <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION>, according to figures provided <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. In a letter to <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> dated April 11, then-Navy Undersecretary <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said the agreement violated <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>'s amendments to the Armed Services Procurement Act because it required the government to buy the engines under contracts not yet negotiated. `` No contracting officer has the authority to bind the government to award future contracts,'' wrote <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON>, who is now secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. From 1990, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> plans to award the contracts `` without the constraints of -LRB- the agreement -RRB-, on the basis of the best value to the government and the taxpayer,'' <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> wrote. The contract was negotiated by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON>, a consultant and a former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> employee, <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> wrote. <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> and the former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> engineer he bribed were given 26-month prison terms June 2 for illegally scheming to help two companies get Pentagon contracts. He and <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlin </PERSON> were each fined $ 25,000 and ordered to serve two years of supervised probation after their release from prison. <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> pleaded guilty to charges that he bribed <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> to provide secret <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> bid information that would help <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Hazeltine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, obtain lucrative contracts to sell electronic equipment to the Pentagon. The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> sought comment from the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> on the agreement. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s press office said Wednesday it was unable to provide information immediately. Both the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>'s office confirmed the existence of the <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> letter. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> vice president for public relations, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jolivette </PERSON>, declined to discuss the issue on the advice of counsel, saying the matter had not yet been resolved.
