<HEAD>Dollar Gains In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar gained against the Japanese yen in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> today, while stock prices rose moderately despite continuing uncertainties in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The dollar ended trading at 143.10 yen, up 0.25 yen from Wednesday's 142.80-yen finish. After opening higher at 142.98 yen, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency ranged between 142.73 and 143.10 yen. <PERSON> Masafumi </PERSON> <PERSON> Koyama </PERSON> with the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> said dollar-buying incentives were stronger than selling incentives, despite an expectation that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> may ease its monetary policy. `` Recent developments in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have a stronger impact, because speculation over a relaxation of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> monetary policy has been an issue for quite a while and is no longer fresh news,'' he said. Theoretically, he said, the market could shift to dollar selling because of the narrowing interest-rate gap between <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` But investors are still buying the dollar, which shows how strong their demand for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency is,'' <PERSON> Koyama </PERSON> said. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed the day at 33,718.29, gaining 91.40 points, or 0.27 percent. The index rose 174.88 points the previous day. Stocks moved higher almost across the board. Dealers attributed the gains to an uptrend begun the previous day, as well as to overnight rises on overseas markets. <PERSON> Kazuyuki </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON>, a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, said the <ORGANIZ