<HEAD>Colorado Health Department Cites Rocky Flats For 25 Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A plant that makes triggers for nuclear bombs was slapped with 25 state health violations the day after federal agents launched an inquiry into illegal dumping and burning of hazardous wastes at the facility. The state's action Wednesday against the <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flats </ORGANIZATION> nuclear plant was independent of the federal investigation and the timing of the two announcements was `` coincidence,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Looby </PERSON>, assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. The state accused the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flats </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION>, of improperly storing wastes, failing to monitor groundwater adequately and storing hazardous wastes in leaking drums. `` The violations involved raised some serious questions in our mind about the overall ability of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> to manage the plant,'' said <PERSON> Looby </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Heintz </PERSON> said he had not seen the health department allegations. `` But I would be surprised if there are any new violations and it is just a matter of interpretation whether or not the deficiencies are cleared up or in the process of being cleared up,'' <PERSON> Heintz </PERSON> said. The plant 16 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> makes plutonium triggers for nuclear bombs. Agents from the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> DOE </PERSON> carried out search warrants there Wednesday for the second day in a row. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said plant employees allegedly concealed contamination and illegally treated, stored and disposed of hazardous and radioactive waste. <PERSON> Looby </PERSON> said the state's order included a total of 24 citations for violation of rules for monitoring hazardous waste in groundwater; unapproved storage of hazardous and mixed wastes; leaking hazardous waste drums; inadequate record-keeping and personnel training, and failure to maintain proper aisle space in waste storage areas. `` No individual instance is a terribly nasty violation,'' said <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelton </PERSON>, director of the health department's Hazardous Materials and Waste Management Division. `` The concern is that in the aggregate, it shows that the facility has a good deal of difficulty in managing its hazardous waste ... in order to stay in compliance with state standards,'' <PERSON> Shelton </PERSON> said. The order gives DOE and <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> 10 days to request a meeting to discuss the order. The state then has a month to finalize the order and to set a compliance deadline for each violation. The maximum penalty for noncompliance is $ 25,000 per violation per day, officials said. Rocky Flats has been dogged by safety and environmental problems since it began operations in 1953, but particularly in recent years. Last year, the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> identified it as the most environmentally hazardous site in the nuclear weapons industry because toxic chemicals contaminate an underground reservoir and threaten nearby city water supplies. In October, the agency closed Rocky Flats' main plutonium reprocessing building for safety violations. Two months later, the agency reported 32 new safety problems at the plant. The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has announced plans to close <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flats </ORGANIZATION> in the next 20 years in a consolidation of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s nuclear weapons plants. In a previous federal probe of a nuclear weapons complex in 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> examined <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> handling of hazardous waste at its <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, reservation. No criminal prosecution resulted.
