<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Larger than the average lobbyist, two cows called on the <ORGANIZATION> Statehouse </ORGANIZATION> with a group of concerned dairy farmers who demanded higher prices for milk in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. Dairy cows <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Kat </PERSON> quietly chewed their cuds while two dozen farmers and their supporters rallied on the Statehouse steps Tuesday. The farmers said high land prices were pushing them out of business and threatening the state's dwindling dairy industry. A proposal in the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> would increase milk prices 2 cents per quart, and the money would be distributed back to state dairy farmers. `` It's either pay now or pay more later,'' said <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> of the 2,200-member Agri-Mark, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s largest dairy cooperative. `` It's not a tax, it's a rate hike.'' The farmers argue that at $ 2.12 per gallon on average, the price of milk in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> is lower than the national average. According to the state agriculture department, there were 3,000 dairy farms in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> in 1960 and only 460 active farms today. Production dropped from 800 million pounds of milk in 1985 to about 470 million pounds last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
