<HEAD>Football Game Canceled By Kennedy Assassination Finally Played</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 25 years after their game was canceled because of President <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s assassination, alumni from two rival high schools took to the gridiron to complete their last football season. <PERSON> Bowie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> high schools have long had the hottest scholastic rivalry in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>. On the morning of Nov. 22, 1963, the schools were holding pep rallies and preparing to cap their seasons with the annual double homecoming. But an assassin's bullet in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> prompted officials to cancel the game. `` If you beat <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON>, that was it. That was your season _ nothing else mattered,'' said <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Peralta </PERSON>, who played wide receiver as a <LOCATION> Bowie </LOCATION> senior in 1963 and coached Wednesday night's game `` I think at the time most of us thought it was important to play the game. You do n't actually complete your high-school season when you ca n't play your main rival.'' Alumni from the schools settled the score Wednesday night with a spirited game of seven-man touch football before 400 spectators at Bowie Stadium. The home team won, 20-8. The contest was n't pretty. The Bowie Bears threw bombs on almost every play and the <ORGANIZATION> Jefferson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Silver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foxes </ORGANIZATION> threw so many laterals that it resembled a volleyball game. But that did n't bother the players. `` It was a lot of fun,'' said <PERSON> Bowie </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Molinar </PERSON>. `` It was just friends against friends.'' The contest brought back memories of that fateful day. `` I was excited,'' <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> alumnus <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> recalled about the week leading to the canceled 1963 game. `` Then our dear president passed away, which was terrible. It was nice to get to play agai