<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who is making his debut in prime-time television tonight with an <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Room </LOCATION> news conference, talked with industry leaders today about the environment and promised new clean-air legislation to `` significantly improve'' the quality of life in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> conferred with industry officials during the morning and arranged an afternoon session with environmentalists to talk about proposed changes in the 1970 Clean Air Act. At 8 p.m. EDT, he planned to meet with reporters to answer questions. In a speech for Ducks Unlimited, a conservation group, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that on Monday he will unveil `` the most sweeping changes to the Clean Air Act since it was last amended 12 years ago. `` It will allow us to recover and restore precious forests, lakes and streams,'' he said. `` And whether Americans live near factories, in cities or in high woodland country, it will significantly improve every North American's quality of life.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told the industry leaders he was still working on his proposal. He promised in February to fix a date certain for reducing smokestack emissions that cause acid rain, which is blamed for killing waterways and forests, particularly in <LOCATION> Northeastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s news conference tonight coincides with the start of the evacuation from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> of all dependents of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government employees and non-essential personnel. `` We have urged all other Americans in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to leave at once,'' White House press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Wednesday. He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy personnel were trying to arrange safe transportation to the airport from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> hotels and other locations. Tonight's news conference marks <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s first question-and-answer session in the stately, chandeliered East Room of the White House. He has met with reporters on numerous occasions in the first 4 -LCB- months of his presidency, but always during the day and never in the formal setting of the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Room </LOCATION>. By scheduling the session in television's prime-time hours, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> assures himself of the largest possible audience. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has held 16 to 23 news conferences so far, depending on how you define a news conference. On Monday, for example, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> fielded questions for 20 minutes in the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> briefing room. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also has held question and answer sessions in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. They have ranged in length from a few minutes to about a half hour. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the White House has been looking for an opportunity for the past two months to have a full-blown East Room news conference. He said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> decided to go ahead now, given the developments in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and his success at the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> summit in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, where he defused a crisis over short-range nuclear missiles and proposed a cutback in Soviet and American combat troops. Traditionally, presidential news conferences run for a half hour but <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> may ignore that, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. He described his boss as `` a president who has trouble confining himself to 30 minutes.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would open with a prepared statement but likely would not make any announcements, as he did Monday in ending military sales to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was not making any special preparations for the news conference, although his Wednesday afternoon schedule was largely clear of appointments. The spokesman said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would meet sometime today with his staff to discuss areas of questions. In another development, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will visit Yellowstone National Park and the Grand Tetons in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> on Monday after proposing legislation to overhaul the Clean Air Act. The press spokesman said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would stop in <LOCATION> Lincoln </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, on the way home Tuesday to deliver a speech on alternative fuels, also part of the environmental package to be unveiled Monday. While at <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>, the president will visit some of the areas charred from the fires last summer that are now undergoing revegetation, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. He will spend the night in a lodge near <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hole </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, and speak Tuesday morning at the <ORGANIZATION> Teton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. His clean air proposal, still in the final stages of preparation, is expected to call for tighter standards for emissions that cause acid rain and for more strictly controlling auto exhaust emissions.
