<FIRST>r w AM-GreatLakes     06-08 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Great Lakes,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission Urges U.S. and Canada to Bar New Species</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An international commission urged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> on Thursday to bar new species of animals from the Great Lakes in an effort to prevent additional harm to the region's delicate ecology `` The integrity of the Great Lakes ecosystem requires the maintenance of a balanced yet dynamic natural system,'' the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, a U.S.-Canadian agency, said in a report on the lakes' environment. `` Introduced species can seriously affect the balance and distribution of native species by altering the structure and developmental patterns of their biological communities,'' it added. The report by the commission noted that there have been continuing concerns about outside species in the lakes, the sea lamprey and smelt in particular. However, in recent years, the number of alien species introduced into the lakes has shown a significant increase. Among the outside species that now threaten the lakes' native life forms are the alewife, the coho salmon, the Asiatic clam, the zebra mussel and the river ruffe. The commission encouraged involvement by the coast guards of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> in controlling the problem, and recommended that the nations `` take steps to prevent the further introduction, particularly the unplanned introduction, of exotic life forms into the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> ecosystem.'' It was the first time the commission had made such a recommendation, said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Bevacqua </PERSON> of the commission's <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office. Some of the outside species were introduced for sport fishing. Others made their way into the lakes as hitchhikers on ships or through extending their range from bodies of water outside the lakes region. Although the new species are controlled by predators in their original homes, many lack predators in the lakes, `` and given an adequate food supply and appropriate life-support systems, ... they can become a serious threat if they outcompete or destroy valuable native species,'' the commission said. The report also warned of increasing concentrations of toxic substances in Great Lakes animals, a reversal of declines recorded in the 1970s. Waterbirds on the lakes, however, were producing more offspring, the commission said. `` Populations that were once declining have increased substantially, and reproductive problems in fish-eating birds are generally confined to specific sites,'' the report said. `` Similarly, increasing bald eagle nesting sites are being reported in the basin.'' The report gave no figures on increased toxic-substance concentration or bird reproduction.
</TEXT>
