<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today that <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>'s school system is unconstitutional because of the spending gap between rich and poor districts, and it ordered the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> to develop a new setup. The ruling has no immediate effect on the 600,000 students; the court, ruling 5-1 with a seventh justice partly concurring and partly dissenting, gave the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> until the end of its 1990 session to come up with a system to even out spending. `` We do not direct the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> to raise taxes. It is their decision how best to achieve efficiency,'' the court said. However, the court said the Legislature _ in what would be a major departure _ must make local tax rates uniform. The ruling was prompted by a lawsuit filed in 1985 by 66 `` property-poor'' districts. They charged that the school-finance system, which depends on property taxes, is not fair in a state where wealth varies widely, from the Appalachian coalfields in eastern <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> to the affluent <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> suburbs. Most states have similar setups in which state spending on education is supplemented by revenue raised locally through property taxes. In 1988, a judge agreed with the plaintiffs that the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> had failed to meet its obligation under the <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constitution </ORGANIZATION> to establish an equitable system of public, or common, schools in either spending or quality. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> largely upheld the judge's finding, saying that <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> children, including those who `` by accident of birth and residence'' live in poor areas, are entitled to the same educational opportunities. `` This obligation can not be shifted to local counties and local school districts,'' the court said. Chief Justice <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON>, writing for the court, said, `` Lest there be any doubt, the result of our decision is that <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>'s entire system of common schools is unconstitutional,'' including its financing regulations. The court said the Legislature has a chance to launch an `` era of educational opportunity which will ensure a strong economic, cultural and political future.'' Gov. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> lauded the ruling. `` We have the opportunity to rebuild, to redefine education in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. And if we fail, we will have failed ourselves, our fellow Kentuckians and particularly our children,'' he said. Schools Superintendent <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> said today was `` the happiest day of my professional life.'' `` Today the court has propelled us from the 19th century to the 21st,'' he said. Justice <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Leibson </PERSON>, in a dissent, said the ruling was confusing, over-reaching and destined to spawn worrisome lawsuits.
</TEXT>
