<HEAD>City Seems Normal; Students Say It Won't Last</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hammers pounded at building sites, table tennis resumed on campuses and soldiers cleaned up the debris. <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> was calm Thursday, almost normal, but students in the pro-democracy movement say it wo n't last. `` The calm is just superficial,'' said a senior at <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Normal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, whose students helped lead the seven weeks of demonstrations. `` With so many people killed, there can not be real calm. It's just a matter of time before the movement peaks again.'' The government said nearly 300 people were killed, but Chinese and foreign diplomats estimate as many as 3,000 died when soldiers with tanks and automatic weapons rolled into the city on Saturday and retook <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> from the students occupying it. Soldiers still fired into the air and at some bystanders Thursday, but far less often than before. Dozens of small restaurants and shops reopened because of the relative quiet, along with a few post offices. Banks remained closed. The <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Daily and <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Evening News were on sale for the first time since Saturday and people formed long lines to buy them. Both were filled with articles denying heavy casualties among civilians and reporting the reopening of businesses. `` There's no news,'' one reader said in disgust. Most residents still stayed away from their jobs. Thousands took bicycle tours of the city, stopping to gape at bullet holes in buildings and bloodstains on walls. Curiosity-seekers clambered over the hulks of tanks burned by citizens. They crowded around hospital morgues, watching families carry out bodies. People walked boldly up to soldiers ringing <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, which has been sealed since Sunday. The troopers politely but firmly refused to answer questions. Residents of the area insisted they were not the same soldiers who stormed the square Saturday night. The evening television news Thursday showed soldiers crouching, using pieces of metal and their hands to clear away ashes and debris. Others hauled the wrecks of buses and tanks off <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s main streets, put twisted road dividers back in place and swept the curbs. A dozen troopers walked west along <LOCATION> Changan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION>, the main street, trimming tree branches away from telephone lines. Whatever the soldiers did, dozens of curious residents watched and commented. `` If we sit around inside, we get too nervous, so we go out to have a look,'' said a restaurant cook who spent the day cycling around the city, exchanging stories with other residents. Minzu Hotel employees said all their guests had left, but several said they reported for work `` to protect the property.'' There have been no reports of looting. `` Life is normal when we go home. We cook, eat,'' said a woman clerk who sat on a pile of wool rugs in a souvenir shop reading a week-old newspaper. `` I spend the day listening to the radio and worrying,'' said a middle-aged professor strolling near his home. Few students still live on <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> campuses, and said they rarely venture out of their dormitories. At <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Normal, some played table tennis while others snacked, read or napped. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> ordered Thursday that schools take steps to resume classes, but the word at <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Normal </LOCATION> was that too few students and teachers remained. `` We do n't know what to do,'' one student said. `` We are waiting for orders, but our leaders are all gone.'' Rumors have circulated that some student leaders were killed, but an activist in hiding told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> all were alive. `` Maybe new leaders will have to emerge,'' another said. `` The movement has n't ended. Things may be calm for awhile, but the army ca n't stay forever. When it goes, we students will protest again.'' He and others said they still seek the resignations of senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> and other hard liners who ordered the crackdown. `` I have no regrets,'' one said. `` No one thought things would come to this, but it would not have if the local citizens had n't supported us We students have great responsibility, and maybe we should apologize to the citizens, but they are responsible too.''
