<HEAD>Tornadoes Hit Louisiana Towns; At Least Two Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with utility service out, woman rescued,
one found dead in trailer home. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BT1, BT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GROSSE TETE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A tornado wiped out nearly a square mile of trailers and other buildings here early today, killing at least two people, and twisters destroyed or damaged nearly 100 homes in <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>, authorities said. The twisters were part of a storm system that also sent tornadoes to numerous other towns overnight and knocked out power throughout southeastern <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. No serious injuries were reported 15 miles away in <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>, where Fire Chief <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Spillman </PERSON> said at least four twisters touched down 19 times, destroying or damaging almost 70 mobile homes and 25 to 30 houses. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuschlag </PERSON>, co-owner of an ambulance service, said his ambulances took at least two dozen people from the <ORGANIZATION> Grosse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tete </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Greensburg </LOCATION> areas to the hospital. Two people were killed in the <LOCATION> Grosse </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tete </LOCATION> area, he said. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lennie </PERSON>, an emergency worker in <LOCATION> Grosse </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tete </LOCATION>, said 35 to 50 homes were damaged by the twister, which struck after 6 a.m., splintering 75-foot trees and knocking out virtually all electricity, gas and telephone service in the town of 750. `` There's more devastation than I have seen in several years of emergency work,'' said <PERSON> Lennie </PERSON>. `` Trailers have been devastated, nice homes completely devastated. Also homes right in the middle of the path have not been touched.'' Police sealed off the area to non-residents while rescue workers using dogs searched wrecked homes for dead or injured, he said. A chainsaw was used to free a woman trapped in the wreckage of a home, authorities said. Mayor <PERSON> Phillilp </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarullo </PERSON> said the twister struck without warning and cut a wide swath of destruction. `` I'd say in 5 to 7 seconds it was over with,'' he said. <PERSON> Flo </PERSON> <PERSON> Nereaux </PERSON>, manager of a truck stop where police set up a command post, said authorities brought two bodies there and were looking for others. `` It wiped out everything in its path. It's torn a body shop up, torn a lot of trailers up,'' she said. `` We have the police out here right now. They're trying to gather up the bodies. We're trying to get a refrigerated truck to put the bodies in.'' One woman apparently died when her trailer flipped over. Her body was found when a bulldozer righted the home, authorities said. In <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Spillman </PERSON> said 400 to 600 people lived in the destroyed or damaged residences. A shelter was set up at a high school for those left homeless. At least six injuries were reported in the <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION> area, none serious. Two minor injuries were reported near <LOCATION> Amite </LOCATION>.
