<FIRST>r w AM-AmericaTomorrow     06-08 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-America Tomorrow,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tomorrow's America: A Look at Those Who Will See a New Century</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most of the Americans who will greet the 21st century are already alive, a group far different from their ancestors who welcomed the arrival of the 1900s, population analysts said Thursday. During the 20th century, the nation's population has grown to unprecedented numbers, people moved south and west, and there have been major shifts in family life and in the status of women. The 21st century is still about a dozen years away but, from a population perspective, the future is now. `` Over 80 percent of the people who will make up the population of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the year 2000 are now alive,'' said a new study by the private <ORGANIZATION> Population </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>. The elderly of the 21st century are already well into their lifespans and the first high school class of the next century is now in the elementary grades, the independent bureau added in a study released Thursday: `` America in the 21st Century: A Demographic Overview.'' At the same time, the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> issued its `` Population Profile of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> 1989,'' looking at the country's current population status The aging of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is likely the most discussed and documented trend, with 29.8 million elderly in the country as of 1987, 12.2 percent of the population, and two-thirds of the group being women, the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> reported. The agency said that this group will continue growing into the next century, jumping to one American in five when the massive post-World War II Baby Boom generation hits senior-citizen status by about the year 2030. That will critically impact health care and retirement income programs, said the <ORGANIZATION> Population </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> study. There will be a relative scarcity of young people to take entry-level jobs, school enrollment could shrink and employers will face a different mix of potential workers. Retraining of older workers may become an economic necessity, said the private group, and there may become a need to ease immigration rules to recruit certain skilled people from other countries. The `` traditional'' family of working husband while the wife stays home with the children has disappeared from the scene. Under half of all families have children, and even in families that have offspring the majority of mothers held jobs outside the home as of 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> reported. At the same time, the <ORGANIZATION> Population </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> said that `` the growing incidence of divorce and out-of-wedlock births has fueled an enormous increase in single-parent families.'' Currently nearly one in four children lives with only one parent, compared with one in 10 in 1960, the private group said. `` The growing concern over child care, elder care and parental leave will continue well into next century,'' the group added. Rapidly growing black and Hispanic populations have also attracted attention in recent years, with the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> reporting that blacks now constitute 12.2 percent of <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> while Hispanics make up 8 percent _ meaning that, although there is some overlap, these two groups now include nearly one in five Americans. `` By 2000, nearly one-third of all school-age children will be from minority populations,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Population </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> reported. The decline in birth rates in recent years means that the growth in the labor force will slacken, but an anticipated `` shortage'' of workers in the next century will be one of the types of employees available, not the total number, the private group said. `` Jobs of the future will demand a moderate to high level of education and training, compared with jobs of the past,'' the group added, and business concerns will center on the potential mismatch between worker skills and job requirements.
</TEXT>
