 Nearly 200 graduating high school seniors refused to have their outdoor commencement postponed because of rain. They demanded their diplomas so they could get on with life, or at least go to the beach. All 206 graduating seniors at <ORGANIZATION> Oconee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> had signed a petition requesting that alternate arrangements be made in case rain threatened the ceremony Tuesday night on the northeast <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>'s school's football field, said senior <PERSON> Tisha </PERSON> <PERSON> Layne </PERSON> When a thunderstorm rolled in minutes before the ceremony, Superintendent S.H. <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> announced the commencement was postponed for one day, and he left. But as many as 1,000 relatives and 197 students crowded into a gymnasium and chanted for <PERSON> Principal </PERSON> <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukes </PERSON> to hand out diplomas informally. `` Twice I tried to call it off,'' <PERSON> Dukes </PERSON> said, `` and then I decided to hand out the diplomas.'' Many of the students were scheduled to leave for <LOCATION> Myrtle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, early Wednesday. An official ceremony was held Wednesday night, with only 27 students in attendance. School board Chairman <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Studdard </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dukes </PERSON> did the right thing. `` In my opinion, a very volatile situation was diffused,'' he said.
