<FIRST>r w AM-CapitalGains     06-08 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capital Gains,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rostenkowski Signals Willingness to Discuss Tax Question with Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, who traditionally has viewed the capital-gains tax preference as the ultimate plaything of the rich, is signaling a change of heart may be on the way _ if the price is right. The price might require President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to back away from his campaign pledge not to raise taxes. Even in that unlikely event, some members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> chairs, said Thursday they would be reluctant to accept any such bargain, even as part of a deficit-reduction measure. For the moment, however, <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., is indicating a willingness to at least discuss the question with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, a former committee colleague `` He does n't like a lower tax rate for capital gains,'' an aide to <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> insisted Thursday. `` But could it ever be acceptable? The answer is yes _ if the president offered in return something so attractive to Democrats that they could n't turn it down,'' added the aide, who spoke only on condition he not be identified by name. The aide elaborated on <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>'s position after the chairman, in separate interviews Wednesday with The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> and The <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>, suggested some kind of capital-gains cut could be acceptable as part of a deficit-reduction plan. The aide said he is not sure <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>'s position has been changed all that much. Despite a long record of criticizing the capital-gains benefit _ `` I'm not about to tell the wage earners in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> that they should pay a higher tax than stockbrokers,'' he said in February, when <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called for the change _ <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> `` never says never,'' the staff member explained. The staff of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Taxation estimates that 80 percent of the tax cut under <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s capital-gains proposal would go to those with incomes over $ 100,000 a year. Those under $ 50,000 would get 8.6 percent. `` That's traditional Republican economics,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.D. </LOCATION>, a Ways and Means member, who said he is not sure the committee is anywhere near a consensus for a capital-gains cut. If the chairman has changed his stance, it apparently is because of the budget deficit. The Ways and <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has been directed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to raise $ 5.3 billion in extra revenues for the budget year that begins next Oct. 1. If several expiring tax benefits are to be renewed, the figure will go higher. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has proposed his own package of relatively minor revenue raisers, including higher Social Security taxes on some state and local government workers and renewal of the expiring tax on telephone service. The president also has called for taxing capital gains _ profits from the sale of stock and certain property _ at a lower rate than applies to wages. Unlike most tax cuts, he insists, such a reduction would raise revenue by encouraging more economic activity. A great number of economists do n't buy that argument over the long run, including some who advise <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. However, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' experts and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s experts agree that such a rate cut would raise more money in the first year simply by encouraging people to unload some investments they had been holding for a while <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> has discussed the possibility of cutting the capital-gains rate for one year, perhaps two. That would be followed by restoring a higher rate but `` indexing'' capital gains so that in the future, an investor would not be taxed on profits that were caused solely by inflation. Congressional economists say such a plan would cost the government revenues after the first year. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, presumably, would be expected to go along with some kind of other tax increase to make up that loss. `` I do n't know if I am prepared to make a tradeoff on capital gains,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Matsui </PERSON>, D-Calif., saying it could cause a return to the abusive tax shelters that were all but wiped out by the 1986 tax overhaul `` And a multiyear reduction would mean we would be sacrificing future years' revenues for one year of deficit reduction.'' <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON> also said good tax policy must not be sacrificed. `` We just went through tax reform, where the tax system was so riddled with loopholes for the rich, and we spent a lot of time correcting that national disgrace,'' he said. Wiping out the special capital-gains benefit and the tax shelters it fed is often cited as one of the major plusses of the 1986 overhaul. <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> has said on several occasions that restoring the capital-gains break would open the door to junking the new law.
