<HEAD>Baker Calls for Soviet Response on NATO Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, saying `` the time is ripe,'' called on Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> today to respond to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposals to slash conventional military forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, in remarks to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is looking for such a response when the Soviet leader visits <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> next week. At last week's <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> summit, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> put forward an elaborate, four-part plan for reducing East-West troop strength and non-nuclear forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` We urged the Soviets to reduce unilaterally their short-range nuclear systems to our levels. Next week, General Secretary <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> can sustain this new spirit by answering our call, by announcing a real cut in Soviet SNF -LRB- Short-Range Nuclear -RRB- forces,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` The time is ripe for Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to respond positively to the opportunities presented by <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s initiatives. Indeed, we look for him to do so when he travels to the <LOCATION> Federal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> next week,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> added. The summit meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> had provided a major lift for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who had been criticized for failing to respond effectively to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s much-publicized arms control initiatives. The session also eased a major controversy between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was able to smooth over the rift between the allies by agreeing to negotiations on the short-range nuclear weapons, which are primarily based in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and, if used, would probably explode on German soil. Under the compromise, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> agreed to enter into the negotiations to achieve a `` partial reduction'' of the weapons once the implementation of the conventional arms agreement was `` under way.'' In the view of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> officials, that also meant that the short-range weapons would not be eliminated, and would remain in the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> arsenal. Under <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal, the Western alliance would agree to a ceiling of 275,000 on the number of Soviet and American troops on foreign soil. That would amount to a reduction of some 30,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops and 325,000 Soviet troops. Besides his proposals on troop cuts, the president proposed that the scope of the talks be broadened to include aircraft, a longstanding Soviet suggestion. In speech to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> last Dec. 7, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said that by the end of 1990, the Soviets would withdraw six tank divisions from the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact nations of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and reduce Soviet troops in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> by 50,000. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> have insisted that <ORGANIZATION> NATO <