<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Press Bjt   06-08 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Press, Bjt,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Time Access but Small Potato News</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 He shows them movies. He feeds them popcorn. He takes them on tours of the first family's living quarters. He knows their first names. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s relationship with reporters is n't a honeymoon, it's a courtship _ or maybe a seduction So far in his presidency, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has given reporters what they most want: access. But he has n't given them enough of what they want almost as much: news. Before his first big-production, prime-time press conference on Thursday night, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> already was meeting often, usually once a week, with reporters in brief daytime sessions. But because his administration had n't framed its own policies on most issues and because <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was cautious in commenting on foreign affairs, what the president had to say did not tend to generate big headlines. `` For a while you had an awful lot of griping, ` Yes, he's a nice guy, he's given us access, but where are the stories?''' commented <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> on Thursday. A senior fellow at the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> studies the relationship between press and government and is the author of `` The <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Reporters.'' `` There was almost a slight longing for the bad old days under <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, where he did n't see them much or respect them, but he gave them lots of stories,'' <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> said. That changed with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s trip to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> last month for a summit with allied leaders and his dramatic proposals for cuts in the standing armies of East and West. As he had promised he eventually would, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> started making presidential-size news. A <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> hand for three decades, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is comfortable with the press. And, a master of detail, he tends to give more complete answers than <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> offered. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> calls reporters who cover the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> by their first names, has some in for off-the-record sessions, sometimes invites a few upstairs for a not-yet-released movie and popcorn and soft drinks. Hardly a week passes that he does n't field their questions. On Monday, when he called a news conference on 15 minutes notice to announce sanctions against <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, reporter <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> arrived late and asked a question that ended, `` Could you explain what the point of doing that is?'' Chided <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>: `` I already did, <PERSON> David </PERSON>. You missed it.'' Then he went on to make his point again. That kind of relaxed relationship is the mark of an expert, <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> said. `` The really good <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> politicians affect an easy-going banter, a light humor, and the one who personified it best was <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>,'' he said. Such politicians, he said, `` know that reporters are very easy to flatter.'' Roosevelt mesmerized the press. He met with reporters in those pre-television days nearly 1,000 times in his 13 years in office. <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> noted that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is following almost all the recommendations of a report last October by the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conferences </ORGANIZATION>, composed of journalists and professors who spent a year studying how to revive a 75-year-old institution. The commission said that under <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> the press conference had fallen into `` a serious state of disrepair.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> formally met reporters infrequently. He let 5 -LCB- months, during the Iran-Contra affair, slide by without a news conference. The commission's principal proposal: `` frequent, routine and undramatic'' news conferences. The panel said presidents should meet with the media twice a month, and do it during daylight hours `` to reduce the temperature and encourage more substantive and useful exchanges.'' It called for limiting prime-time news conferences to six a year. <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> said `` the massive news conference'' generally does n't generate much news `` It is n't a very good way to get information out,'' he said. `` It's a way for the people to see a president in action, so it serves him and it serves the egos of the press corps. But there are better ways to make news.''
