<HEAD>Alaska Senator Criticizes Housing Allowance Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Republican senator lashed out Thursday at the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> system of providing a housing allowance to military personnel living outside installations, charging that the current policy is unfair to residents of economically-depressed areas. `` I've never seen worse stupidity in my life,'' Sen. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, said at a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations defense subcommittee hearing on military manpower. The object of <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' ire was the Variable Housing Allowance, a stipend that military personnel forced to live off base during a three-to-four year stint can use to help defray the cost of housing. The allowance is based on 80 percent of local housing costs and changes annually depending on the housing market. For military personnel with mortgages or extended leases and living in the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, two areas hardest hit by problems in the oil industry, the allowance has decreased as housing prices have dropped. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> was particularly angered by the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s recent decision to distribute $ 77 million in surplus allowances equally among all recipients rather than targeting those who have had their allowance cut. `` This is the most unfair system I've ever seen,'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said. Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berteau </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> for resource management and support, barely getting a word in, said the effect of penalizing those in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> is `` the exception rather than the rule.'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> also criticized the fiscal 1990 budget's proposed level of $ 3.609 billion for stationing military personnel and their dependents overseas, an inc