officials still retain government jobs. Pickup 3rd pvs, ``Only two...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Polish voters have rejected Prime Minister <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> and 32 other top officials of the communist coalition who ran unopposed in elections, according to official results released today. The results by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> indicated that 33 of the 35 high officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and its allies were rejected in the parliamentary election Sunday. The candidates failed to get the 50 percent of the vote required because many citizens crossed out their names on the ballot. Despite their losses, <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> and the others will retain their regular government posts. But the victory by Solidarity candidates gives the opposition power to veto legislation and even prevent that veto from being overridden. Only two coalition candidates were were elected: <ORGANIZATION> Peasant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Mikolaj </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozakiewicz </PERSON>, who is a communist ally but who has gained a reputation for independence; and communist administrative law judge <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Zielinski </PERSON>. The results were released as Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> to meet with Interior Minister Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> and other officials to discuss how the rejected candidates might be seated in spite of their defeat. Solidarity's candidates won an overwhelming victory in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s first democratic parliamentary elections in 40 years. The union led the opposition after it was legalized under a pact with the government. In all, 165 deputies were elected to the 460-member Sejm, or lower house, in the first round: 160 from Solidarity and five from the communist or allied parties. In the new, freely elected 100-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, 92 senators were picked in the first round, all from Solidarity. Besides <PERSON> Kozakiewicz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Zielinski </PERSON> from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> list, just three party or allied candidates running for 264 contested seats reserved for the party coalition managed to get 50 percent in the first round. The other 261 will be decided in runoffs June 18. By comparison, only one of the Solidarity-backed candidates to the Sejm running for 161 seats reserved for the opposition failed to get more than 50 percent in the first round. Solidarity hopes to win that seat and the eight remaining <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seats in the second round. It also says it will back certain sympathetic communist or allied candidates in the runoff to build on its electoral success. Solidarity has indicated it would like to find a compromise to seat the rejected communist officials in keeping with its previous agreement to allow the communists and their allies 65 percent of the Sejm. The union is also worried the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> might lose its importance if top party leaders were absent. In addition to <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, the seven other members of the 17-member Politburo who were on the communist coalition were also rejected. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s leader, Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, was quoted today by a British newspaper, the Independent, as conceding that election results were `` not favorable'' to the communist <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. But he was quoted as saying the outcome would not hinder `` the bold historical experiment we have begun'' and calling for further `` dialogue and compromise.'' It was <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>'s first public comments on the election. He also said the next parliamentary election, set for 1993, should be totally free and that the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> would have to consider relinquishing power in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> if its candidates again lose.
