<HEAD>Couple, Delayed 23 Years, Weds in Hospital Room</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After 23 years, in which he and his wife-to-be raised eight children and collected 19 grandchildren, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Amerson </PERSON> finally got married. But it was n't easy. The couple, stymied in 1966 by a now defunct <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> law prohibiting interracial marriages, were almost delayed again, this time by health problems. But the wedding went on Wednesday, although the setting was not quite what <PERSON> Amerson </PERSON> and his bride and longtime companion, <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON>, had planned. The vows were spoken at <LOCATION> Amerson </LOCATION>'s bedside in the coronary intensive care unit at <ORGANIZATION> Grady </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, where <PERSON> Amerson </PERSON> had been admitted Tuesday night after complaining of chest pains. A half-dozen hospital staffers looked on as <PERSON> Amerson </PERSON> and his bride, both 48, tied the knot in a brief ceremony, standing before a minister beside the bed. The bride, dressed in a pink and white print dress and white jacket, glided into the room on the arm of registered nurse <PERSON> Rochelle </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hersch </PERSON>, who arranged the ceremony and also served as witness. The bride carried a bouquet of pink and white carnations; the groom, who suffered a heart attack two years ago, wore pajamas and was attached to a heart monitor. The Amersons had planned to be married at their home in southeast <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> on Wednesday, their 23rd anniversary together. The Amersons met in 1965 and began living together a year later. They would have wed then, he said, but <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> law prohibited interracial marriages until 1979. So they decided to change her name legally, and she took his. `` We had always wanted a marriage license,'' <PERSON> Amerson </PERSON> said. `` So this anniversary I planned to give her a lice