<HEAD>University City Moves To Tighten Up on Animal Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The City Council has endorsed the idea of appointing a commissioner to oversee all experiments on animals and make unannounced laboratory inspections. The council Monday also agreed that all animal experiments here should be required to meet federal standards for care and testing of animals. Currently, only those institutions getting federal funds are subject to the standards. The proposals were drawn up by a panel consisting of a veterinarian, a lawyer and a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> professor. City Manager <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> said the city solicitor has been asked to draft an ordinance and a vote could come early next week. The animal-rights measure would affect <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> along with 11 other businesses and institutions. Most of the institutions, including <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> MIT </ORGANIZATION>, already are subject to federal standards for humane care and experimentation.
