<HEAD>VOA Beaming TV Signal to Chinese Military Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In response to the Chinese crisis, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government's <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> is beaming television signals to the People's Republic, the first time it has ever taken such a step, the director said Thursday. The signal is going directly to about 2,000 satellite dishes operated largely by the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, although there is no way to tell whether the transmission is being watched by the military or passed along other channels, said <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> is receiving the signal `` loud and clear'' on a satellite dish in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, he said. The transmission began Tuesday. The broadcast of news to the military is significant because of reports that units backing the pro-democracy demonstrators may have exchanged fire with units supporting the crackdown. `` We are sending a television signal that is available to every major military installation in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview. The signal originates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and bounces off satellites over the Indian and <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceans </ORGANIZATION>, covering all of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` It makes available to the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> military information about what is going on in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, information that may not otherwise be available to the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> military,'' he said. Television and radio sets are not built to receive direct satellite signals. The transmissions must be received by satellite dishes and re-broadcast in a signal accessible to individual receivers, said <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION>, which broadcasts radio programs in many languages around the world, including transmissions targeted at communist nations, has never used a television signal before, said <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>. `` It seemed like the right thing to do,'' said <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>, who made the decision and informed a special <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> task force monitoring events in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deparment </ORGANIZATION> is aware of it. No one has objected.'' The <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> normally beams eight hours of radio broadcasts daily in Mandarin to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, but increased that to 11 hours in response to the student demonstrations in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. `` Chinese authorities have said that we have a regular listening audience of 60 million. We believe that we are over 100 million now. We are clearly the most pervasive non-Chinese source of news in the country,'' said <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION>'s television image shows a broadcaster reading the news, as the Chinese-language script scrolls across the lower part of the screen. <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> has not attempted to broadcast television images of the demonstrations or the aftermath. During the unrest, said <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> authorities have tried to jam <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> radio broadcasts. They have not tried to jam <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION>'s English language broadcasts. <ORGANIZATION> VOA </ORGANIZATION> maintains a bureau with two correspondents in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, and uses other Western news services, which have been reporting a different story than the official <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> media. `` The Chinese media have been very dishonest about the student demonstrations and the role of the military,'' said <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>. `` Chinese media have said there were 300 dead, and that they were mostly soldiers, which is not true. The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> says 3,000 people died,'' he said. Some Western sources in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> have estimated the dead at 7,000.
