<FIRST>u w AM-ToxicChemicals Bjt   06-08 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toxic Chemicals, Bjt,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disputed List Says Indistrial Plants Pose Cancer Risk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Bly LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel chairman Thursday distributed federal data identifying 205 industrial plants as increasing cancer risks through release of airborne toxic chemicals. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> quickly disputed his interpretations. An <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the information was old and incomplete, and complained it was `` highly irresponsible'' to use it as `` reflective of risks in the real world.'' However, Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> environment subcommittee, said that even potentially inaccurate figures should be released because they `` indicate the enormity of the problem'' and represent a `` stunning demonstration of the urgency of the public health threat.'' <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, D-Calif., said at a news conference that toxic chemicals present a cancer risk near the plants at least a thousand-fold greater than levels accepted by experts The plants on the list, compiled by the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, pose at least a 1-in-1 ,000 cancer risk to people getting maximum exposure for a lifetime, while the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> deems a risk of more than 1-in-a-million as unacceptable `` It's public information,'' Rep. <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Molinari </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, told the news conference in defending release of the data. `` The public has a right to know,'' added Rep. <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>, <PERSON> Molinari </PERSON>, <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sikorski </PERSON>, D-Minn., combined release of the figures with an announcement that they have introduced legislation to control airborne toxic chemical releases The bill would limit emissions from industrial sources and motor vehicles, attempt to prevent accidental releases, protect the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION>, which have been seriously damaged by airborne toxic chemicals, and control emissions from small businesses. <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> plans to incorporate the legislation into a comprehensive clean air bill that also would address urban pollution and acid rain. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is expected to introduce its own clean air proposals next week, including what <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> described as a `` strong air toxics component.'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said the data on the individual facilities were complied to develop computer models to compare health risks from one plant to another. `` The figures ... were never used to reflect risks in the real world,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said, and `` any suggestion those data are reflective of risks in the real world is an entirely erroneous interpretation ... a highly irresponsible interpretation.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said, `` To imply that these estimates depict the real risks of living near one of the plants is not just exaggeration but an outright misuse of data to deliberately alarm people.'' The estimates assume a 70-year lifetime exposure to a chemical at its maximum exposure level at a plant. The figures indicated that 205 facilities posed cancer risks for the most exposed individuals that may exceed 1 in 1,000. Forty-five of these facilities had maximum individual risks of greater than 1 in 100, and one had at least a 1-in-10 risk. The estimates represent evaluations of the maximum individual cancer risk that might arise from the inhalation of a single toxic air pollutant from an individual facility. For example, a risk estimate of 1 in 1,000 means that one person out of 1,000 could be expected to contract cancer from maximum exposure to a single pollutant. <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> said that because of the potential inaccuracy of the data, he did n't know whether the problems at individual plants should be considered worse than the figures showed or, on the other hand, `` not serious.'' But he said there is a real possibility the problem is worse than indicated because the data were limited. For instance, the information only measures cancer risks, but not other potential hazards such as birth defects, nervous system damage or respiratory disease. The figures also do not reflect the combined cancer risk of different air toxics that might be released by a single plant. Also, only the cancer risk from direct inhalation of air toxics is evaluated, although numerous studies indicate the potential contamination of crops in nearby areas, or accumulation of toxics in the food chain, can exceed the risk from breathing the chemicals. In addition, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> did not evaluate some toxics, including benzene and coke oven emissions. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said the worst plant on the list was the <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> butadiene plant in <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Neches </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, with at least a 1-in-10 risk of cancer. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> labeled the estimate `` totally unsupported by any technical and scientific facts or by employee health records.''
</TEXT>
