<HEAD>Syrians, Christian Resume Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian gunners shelled the Christian enclave north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> on Thursday as three Arab foreign ministers opened talks in <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> to try to end three months of fighting in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Police said two civilians were wounded during the sporadic daylong hostilities. Syrian gunners, deployed in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, fired more than 100 howitzer shells in an apparent effort to prevent <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> from receiving arms supplies by sea, police said. A police spokesman, who can not be named under standing rules, said the shells exploded around the Christian ports of <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> and Byblos. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s gunners, entrenched in the 310-square-mile enclave, unleashed a howitzer barrage at sundown aimed at Syrian gun positions in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s seaside district, police reported. `` It's a limited retaliation aimed at the sources of Syrian fire,'' said a communique from <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s headquarters. The police spokesman said gun battles broke out at nightfall between <LOCATION> Syrian </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> units across <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s dividing Green Line in the battle-scarred old commercial district straddling the port. The latest round of fighting in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 14-year civil war began on March 8. Since then, 363 people have been killed and 1,432 wounded. In the Syrian capital, President <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON> met with foreign ministers <PERSON> Abdel </PERSON> <PERSON> Latif </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Filali </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bouallam </PERSON> <PERSON> Bsayeh </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> and Prince <PERSON> Saud </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Faisal </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> 