thdrawal of Israeli forces that control, along with allied militias, a six - to 10-mile buffer zone in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> to prevent guerrilla attacks on northern Israeli settlements <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> troops are stationed across 70 percent of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> under a 1976 Arab League peace-keeping mandate. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> and other Christian leaders accuse the Syrians of failing in their mandate by siding with Moslems against Christians in the civil war. The leftist daily newspaper <ORGANIZATION> As-Safir </ORGANIZATION> said Syrian vice president <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Halim </PERSON> <PERSON> Khaddam </PERSON> Wednesday dismissed <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> as `` not a man of dialogue. ... He does not have a clear-cut political horizon.'' It said <PERSON> Khaddam </PERSON> made the remarks in <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> to a delegation from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s Syrian-controlled northern province of <LOCATION> Akkar </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Khaddam </PERSON> said Syrian troops were `` prepared to remain in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> for another 14 years if need be to achieve justice.'' He was referring to political reforms demanded by Syrian-backed Moslem leaders who have been fighting fellow Christians since 1975 to achieve equality in running <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s affairs.
