<HEAD>Reports: Monk Says He Saw Up to Six U.S. POWs in Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Japanese <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monk recovering from 14 years of imprisonment in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> said he may have seen <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prisoners of war at a re-education camp, according to news reports Thursday. <PERSON> Ganshin </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON>, 65, told Japanese reporters there were `` five or six'' prisoners of war who spoke English at the camp where he was held for the last seven years. Vietnamese political prisoners called them Americans, he said. An official of the Vietnamese Embassy in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> called <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON>'s remarks groundless `` Our government has repeatedly discussed that issue in the past. There are no more American POWs'' in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, the official told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on condition of anonymity. <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> as saying he did not know what the living conditions of the purported POWs were like because they lived in a separate building. But he said they had been treated horribly and had been tortured, <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> reported. The location of the camp was not disclosed. <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> said the prisoners were put to work in construction projects, the news agency said. Hospitalized for ailments resulting from his confinement, <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> has been too ill to talk until now, 4 -LCB- months after his return to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Televison </ORGANIZATION> said. He is hospitalized in <LOCATION> Sapporo </LOCATION> on Hokkaido, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s northernmost island. <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON>'s daughter, <PERSON> Keiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Takatsuka </PERSON>, informed the <LOCATION> U.S. </