<HEAD>First Walkout Stuns Soviet Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About two dozen Baltic parliamentarians angry about central control of their republics stormed out of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Thursday in a dramatic demonstration that lawmakers are no longer cogs in the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> machinery. `` Comrades! Comrades! I ask you to be calm because this is not all so simple,'' an exasperated President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> cried as the deputies left the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s Palace of Congresses. It was the first walkout of the raucous <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies session that began May 25 and is scheduled to end Friday, and it underscored the increasingly unpredictable nature of <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> politics It also reflected the heated opposition by some deputies to the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> establishment that runs the session and nominates committee members and other officials. In other tough talk Thursday, a radical economist said the country should cut aid to the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s Latin American allies and pay farmers foreign currency to help avert economic collapse. Another deputy said the country was on the brink of ecological disaster. Soviet television, which broadcast the session live to millions, showed about 25 deputies storming out. The Baltic legislators made the dramatic move after objecting to formation of a committee by the 2,250-member <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that will decide whether laws conform to the Soviet Constitution. They said the committee could encroach on their republics' right to self-determination and ability to veto laws passed by the central government. `` Our electors ordered us to take care of the sovereignty of our republics,'' said <PERSON> Romas </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gudaitis </PERSON>, a writer and deputy from <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>. `` We consider the elections of the <ORGANIZATION> Constitutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to be without purpose and we will not take part in them.'' <PERSON> Gudaitis </PERSON> called the committee a remnant of the `` Stalin empire'' and part of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s attempts to `` control and oppress national problems by an iron glove.'' Lithuanian deputies, among the most vocal at the parliamentary session, led the walkout, the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said representatives of the two other Baltic republics, <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>, also objected to the committee. But it was not immediately clear if they joined the Lithuanian walkout. The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> voted overwhelmingly to form the committee on Thursday, but 433 deputies were against and 61 abstained, including <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>'s delegation. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said he would consult with the deputies who objected and that the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would vote on the committee membership Friday morning. The Baltic representatives contend the Soviet takeover of their nations in 1940 went against the people's will and believe Moscow-based ministries have ruined their environment and economy. Many Baltic residents are demanding autonomy from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in all but defense and security. In a direct clash with the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, the legislatures of <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> have proclaimed the right to veto laws approved by the central government in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Later Thursday, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told reporters to leave the hall and asked that TV cameras be turned off. The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> then went into its first closed session, its topic undisclosed. <PERSON> Alexei </PERSON> <PERSON> Yastrebov </PERSON>, a deputy from the <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> area of <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>, said in a telephone interview the closed session involved discussion of violence in <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION>. At least 71 people have been killed in a five-day rampage involving ethnic Uzbeks and the <PERSON> Meskhi </PERSON> <PERSON> Turk </PERSON> minority in the southern Soviet republic. More than 9,000 <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> troops have been sent in and a curfew was imposed. <PERSON> Yastrebov </PERSON> said the deputies were asked whether they believe `` more decisive measures'' are needed to end the unrest but that a decision was postponed until Friday. He said he could not spell out what other measures the deputies could approve. In earlier debate, economist <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Shmelev </PERSON> said Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>'s call on Wednesday for extensive defense cuts and government relief for almost 40 million Soviets living in poverty will fall far short of solving the country's woes. <PERSON> Shmelev </PERSON> said Soviet farmers should be motivated to work harder by offering them pay in foreign currency with which they could buy hard-to-get goods. <PERSON> Shmelev </PERSON> also called for a cut in aid to <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Quoting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> estimates that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> spends between $ 6 and $ 8 billion on activities there, especially in aid to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, he said `` no one understands what a significant portion of that money is spent on.''
