uries suffered by a prisoner who was beaten while in the custody of <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriffs' deputies. The 1976 beating of <PERSON> Salvatore </PERSON> <PERSON> Marchese </PERSON> by an unidentified person who was admitted to his locked holding cell was the subject of a strongly worded 1985 ruling by the 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. The court cited <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>' `` failure to provide a trained and disciplined county law enforcement agency'' or to investigate the beating incident. <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> had testified that he did not know about the incident and therefore would not have been able to investigate it. But the appellate court said he remained legally liable and that his failure to order and direct an investigation and to punish those responsible `` served to confirm the existence of an unstated ` policy' of toleration of illegal brutality toward any county prisoner who had threatened the life of a sheriff's deputy.''
