<HEAD>Committee Hears Support, Opposition For Shipping Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee heard opposing views Thursday on a bill to reduce regulation in the shipment of goods by sea between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ports, one of the last heavily regulated forms of transportation. The measure would primarily affect the shipment of goods to and from <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> and other island territories. It would put all such traffic under the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maritime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Currently, the <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> regulates some shipments that start out on rail or truck. In some cases, shippers can choose which federal agency they want to have oversee their rates. `` Some island communities feel they are captive to those few carriers that serve their island, while other domestic trade areas have vigorous competition that help restrain rates,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.C. </LOCATION>, chairman of the merchant marine subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> and Fisheries. `` This bill deregulates a great deal,'' said <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, `` but, frankly, it retains the concept of economic regulations where the public interest demands a degree of oversight.'' In the first of two scheduled hearings on the measure, domestic ocean carriers varied in their reactions to the bill. A hearing next week is to include federal regulators, state representatives and shippers. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Knapp </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> opposed the bill, saying regulation by the maritime commission would prohibit shipments by contracts which are allowed under <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION> regulations. `` This bill would severely compromise competition in the interstate transportation marketplace and it would unduly restrict a carrier's ability to tailor services to shipper requirements in a timely manner,'' <PERSON> Knapp </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, president of Gulf Puerto Rican Transport, supported a provision in the bill that would prohibit the government of <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> from requiring its agencies to use vessels operated by the state-owned carrier even though its prices may be higher that other carriers. <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Tropical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates 12 vessels serving the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> and several <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> countries, said having two agencies regulate shipping has resulted in `` confusing and conflicting regulations.'' He said some shippers have tried to avoid paying for services by filing complaints that their shipments should have been covered by a different federal agency.
