<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An aide to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Defense Secretary <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> said Thursday the one-year timeframe President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> set for an East-West accord on cutting conventional forces and arms in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> was more a goal than a deadline. West German Gen. <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> <PERSON> Altenburg </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s panel of allied commanders, had questioned the timetable as <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> and his colleagues held their spring meeting at <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. `` It's a real challenge,'' <PERSON> Altenburg </PERSON> told reporters. `` It's optimistic, indeed Unrealistic? I do n't know. ... If we make it in 12 months, I do not know.'' At a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> summit in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> last week, the allies agreed to a proposal advanced by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on specific cuts in troops and combat aircraft. His new plan came in response to a flurry of recent arms control initiatives by Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants accord reached within six to 12 months at East-West talks in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> to cut <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet troops in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to 275,000 each and cut about 750 combat planes from <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> forces and 3,000 from the seven-nation <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION>. The president said that if <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> withdraws 30,000 troops from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> withdraws 325,000, each side then would have 275,000 troops remaining. <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON> discussed the timetable with the defense ministers. A <LOCATION> Cheney </LOCATION> aide, briefing reporters, agreed it was `` ambitious'' to expect a conventional arms accord within a year. But, said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity: `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> put it up as a goal, not a deadline.'' He said success at the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> talks hinged on Soviet willingness to reach an accord. `` It's up to the Soviets, now.'' The aide pointed to an improved East-West disarmament climate and said, `` We are moving already much faster than before.'' The ministers will end their two-day meeting Friday by reaffirming the goal for all <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> nations to increase annual defense budgets by 3 percent after inflation. The <LOCATION> Cheney </LOCATION> aide said that although most members _ including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ will not achieve that goal this year, the defense chiefs agreed it would be unwise to drop 3 percent as an objective. This week, <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> officials held their first talks on how to implement <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s aircraft proposal: how and where to cut 750 combat aircraft from <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> air forces and which aircraft should be scrapped. East and West are already negotiating cuts in such armaments as tanks and artillery throughout <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> at the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> talks that began this year. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> added troops and combat aircraft in response to a flurry of recent arms control initiatives by Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Officials said the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> panel considering aircraft cuts will meet weekly until September to beat what <PERSON> Altenburg </PERSON> termed the `` very severe time factor'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> put on his proposals. `` For instance, how is this to be broken down among the different nations? We have to consider the role each nation has.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said there was `` general agreement'' among the ministers not to reduce British and French planes that can carry conventional or nuclear bombs. Also excluded, they said, must be the 72 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> F-16 jets <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> will be moving from <LOCATION> Torrejon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> to a base in southern <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. The move follows <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s decision to end a basing accord with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The ministers reviewed on Thursday their efforts to maintain an equitable sharing of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s defense costs _ an issue that has generated criticism in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that many <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies do not pull their weight in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>.
