<HEAD>Bush Indicates He Plans Hard-Line Approach on Air Standards</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 12th graf pvs, These standards, with
comment from Senate Democratic Leader Mitchell; picks up 13th graf, Speaking
to</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> indicated Thursday he plans a hard-line approach on new clean-air standards that will `` significantly improve'' the quality of life of all North Americans. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who will unveil his clean-air package Monday, met with industry leaders who said they pleaded against coming up with standards too tough to be affordable. `` We urged him to make certain that, when the dust settles on clean air, that we have a healthy economy left,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fay </PERSON>, administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> Clean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Working </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a business coalition. `` We'll have to wait until Monday to see whether or not the point got through,'' <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> said after he and other industry officials met with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at the White House. Later, at a session with environmental leaders, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> indicated he was ready to move ahead with strong measures, participants said. `` He said that he agreed this is a freight train coming down the track,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Frampton </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Wilderness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. `` He felt that he strongly personally wanted to be out front on this.'' <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION>, said `` We are calling on him to again do a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. It is time for him to exercise leadership and call for strong measures to protect the health of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people.'' She was referring to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s dramatic call last month for unilateral troop cuts in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> She said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was given information on air quality in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, where he has a vacation home. `` He was shocked to know that last summer, there were many days in which there were serious health problems from ozone smog,'' she said. White House aides, as well as participants at both the industry and environmental meetings, insisted <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has not made up his mind on many aspects of the package, the first major overhaul of the 1970 Clean Air Act in 12 years. Administration aides, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said, however, that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had already decided on many key parts of the legislation _ including tough new standards for cleaning up smokestack emissions that cause acid rain, changes that would prove costly to industry. The president has also decided on rigid new standards to prevent chemical contamination of the air. These standards will be far-reaching, extending to hundreds of categories of businesses, ranging from paint factories to bakeries, the sources said. Such suggestions prompted praise from congressional Democrats even before <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> submitted his proposal. `` He has wholly reversed the position of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration on this subject,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. Speaking to a hunters' conservation group, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> reinforced the contention that his proposals would prove costly to industry and be wide-ranging. `` For too long, we've focused on cleanup and penalties after the damage is already done. It's time to reorient ourselves using technologies and processes that reduce or prevent pollution _ to stop it before it starts. In the 1990s, pollution prevention will go right to the sources,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Power plants and other industries that burn coal in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, many of which disperse their pollutants through tall smokestacks without technological controls, will be a key target of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s clean-air attack, the sources said These emissions have been cited as a major cause in the acid-rain pollution that afflicts lakes and wildlife in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Northeastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In his remarks to <ORGANIZATION> Ducks </ORGANIZATION> Unlimited, a conservation group of waterfowl hunters that seeks to protect and preserve wetlands, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> declared: `` I will unveil the most sweeping changes to the Clean Air Act since it was last amended 12 years ago.'' `` It will allow us to recover and restore precious forests, lakes and streams. And whether Americans live near factories, in cities, or in high woodland country, it will significantly improve every North American's quality of life.'' <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, said the industry leaders who met with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` asked the president for a flexible solution that would be cost effective. And he said he had n't made up his mind on a lot of factors yet.'' `` He did n't make any commitments on anything. We need to have a bill that's on an economically sound basis,'' he said. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> voiced some skepticism toward one feature that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said will be in the legislation _ a program to encourage alternate motor fuels such as alcohol blends. `` We need more studies on alternate fuels,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. He said that car engines that can accept alcohol blends use greater volumes of fuel than gasoline-only engines _ suggesting either larger fuel tanks in vehicles or the building of more service stations. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lesher </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZ