<FIRST>r w AM-MilitaryRecruiting     06-08 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military Recruiting,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Studies Say Services Can Save Money If They Rely on Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The armed forces can save money if they rely on advertising to obtain recruits instead of more recruiters or cash bonuses, according to studies released Thursday. And at least in the case of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, they said the advertising should be placed in national magazines and local newspapers first, with television the next priority and local radio last. The report on military advertising was issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Rand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a Pentagon-supported think tank based in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. It was asked to study the issue by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s manpower office. Rand issued two studies, one focusing on <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> advertising efforts and the other assessing whether the services should do their own ads or whether `` joint'' ads with the other armed forces work as well. The studies, focusing on military advertising campaigns from 1981 to 1984, were done by researchers <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dertouzos </PERSON> and <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Polich </PERSON>. The research dealing with the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> found advertising does make a difference in an era of the all-volunteer military and cuts in the ad budget will hurt. `` The empirical results show that, in general, advertising expenditures in a given month have a significant and immediate effect on the number of high-quality enlistments in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>,'' the study said. `` We estimated the marginal cost of recruiting a high-quality person through increased advertising to be between $ 5,000 and $ 6,000. The marginal cost of achieving the same goal by increasing the recruiting staff was about $ 5,700, and the cost of using cash bonuses was much higher, about $ 16,000 per recruit.'' There also appear to be significant differences among the media in their cost effectiveness, at least for the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, the study continued. `` National magazine and local newspaper advertising are the most cost effective in promoting short-run enlistment responses, costing $ 2,000 and $ 3,400 per additional recruit. National broadcasting purchases also have strong effects but ... appear to cost somewhat more than the print media, $ 7,000 to $ 10,000 per marginal recruit. `` At the other extreme, local radio has no detectable effect on short-run enlistments.'' In 1984, the study said, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> spent $ 45 million on recruiting ads and used two-thirds of that money for TV spots. As for the issue of individual `` service'' advertisements as opposed to `` joint'' ads, the second study concluded both types `` appear to be very powerful tools'' and in general can produce a new recruit for roughly the same outlay of cash. The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, however, do appear to benefit the most from joint ads, while the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> seem to do the best with individual ads. `` But in general, ... the gains of any one branch do not seem to come at the expense, in terms of lost recruits, of any othr,'' the study said. `` Each branch gained recruits from the civilian population rather than at the others' expense.''
</TEXT>
