e ethnic violence have been arrested. The official radio said that shooting and arson attempts continued Wednesday night in the regional center of <LOCATION> Fergana </LOCATION>, with a population of more than 200,000. More than 400 houses, most of them belonging to <PERSON> Meskhi </PERSON> <PERSON> Turks </PERSON>, had been burned down. The official reports did not specify which ethnic group was responsible for the attacks in <LOCATION> Kokand </LOCATION>, but it was likely Uzbeks because the Meskhis have been the victims of most of the violence and many of them already have been evacuated. Uzbek sources said the violence, which started with a dispute over the price of strawberries in a bazaar, erupted because of smoldering resentment among Uzbeks over what they see as preferential treatment of the minority. The dispute led to a wave of `` pogroms, arson, beatings and murder, accompanied by harassment and rape in conjunction with insolent marauding, resistance to police and internal security forces,'' <PERSON> Kadyrov </PERSON> said. `` Passions are still boiling,'' <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> added. The Uzbek grassroots movement <PERSON> Berlik </PERSON> called on the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to remedy living conditions, which it said was an underlying cause of the bloodshed. The activists claim cotton production quotas imposed by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has forced <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION> to neglect food crops. Meanwhile, the campaign to boost cotton production has forced farms to poison the enviromment with vast quantities of chemical fertilizers and pesticides, they say.
