<HEAD>HUD To Reopen Investigation Into Long Island Housing Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with Kemp ordering investigation reopened, McGann
taking administrative leave, other details; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> will reopen a probe into an alleged scheme to rig the awarding of federally subsidized housing in <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> announced Thursday. `` I have asked the inspector general to reopen his investigation into the situation surrounding <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> McGann </PERSON> and the allocation of federally subsidized housing in the village of <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said in a news release. Mrs. <PERSON> McGann </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s region II adminstrator, is at the center of the controversy. Her son, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> McGann </PERSON>, was among those chosen to purchase a $ 44,500 house in the program. Mrs. <PERSON> McGann </PERSON> is a village board member and last year was appointed <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s Region II administrator. A cousin of Republican Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, a longtime resident of <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, also benefitted from the program by buying a home for $ 40,000, according to a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> audit. Mrs. <PERSON> McGann </PERSON> asked for and was granted an administrative leave, <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said Thursday. She will continue to collect her $ 68,500 annual salary, according to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nipp </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> McGann </PERSON> could not be reached for comment Thursday. A woman answering the phone in her office said Mrs. <PERSON> McGann </PERSON> would not be at work. The new investigation was triggered by a report in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> that officials in <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, a predominantly white <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> village, had distributed federally subsidized homes to politically connected people and excluded blacks between 1980 and 1984. The Times based its story on a 1984 <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> audit of the program. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> also announced high-level <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> employees will no longer be allowed to serve on state or local government boards, agencies or panels, and no <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> employee at any level may serve on any such body that does business with the department. In addition, <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said in the statement that <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> discretionary funds will be targeted at ending homelessness, enforcing fair housing and creating enterprise zones, for example. The Times report noted that <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> had persuaded former Housing Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Piece </PERSON> to earmark $ 425,000 from the fund for a swimming pool in the oceanfront community. The pool has not been built because the project has been tied up in local politics. <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>'s cousin, <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciccimarro </PERSON>, paid $ 40,000 for one of the subsidized houses, according to the 1984 audit. On Thursday, <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> denied any involvement, and termed the program `` excellent.'' `` I know of no abuse and I know of no preferential treatment,'' <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> told a news conference. `` I wrote no applications nor made any applications on -LRB- people's -RRB- behalf. Had they asked me I would have. I thought the program was a good program.'' Under the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> program, <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, which has a population of 4,200 and is 97 percent white, received enough money to build 44 homes to be sold at $ 40,000 to $ 64,000 each. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> proposed that 17 of the 22 houses to be built during the project's second phase be sold to blacks from nearby areas, but none were. The <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> houses were supposed to be advertised in local newspapers to reach lower-income buyers, especially minorities. But some residents were tipped off, and by the time the ads appeared, 22 buyers had been selected, the Times said. <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> said he did not believe there were tips or that no houses were purchased by members of minority groups. He blamed the Times story on `` a disgruntled former employee,'' <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Scully </PERSON>, who was <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>'s village clerk at the time. `` It's obvious that the former village clerk, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Scully </PERSON>, has changed his story in order to attack his former associates on the village board for whatever reasons, and that saddens me,'' <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Scully </PERSON> told the Times that he misled <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials probing the program in 1984. He said Mrs. <PERSON> McGann </PERSON> had called him to inquire about a HUD house for her son, and also said he had covered up for her. <PERSON> Scully </PERSON> did not immediately return a message left on his answering machine. <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> said the story was based primarily on a 5-year-old preliminary audit. `` I've been given to believe that the inspector general's final report did not concur with that 5-year-old preliminary audit, and found no evidence of wrongdoing,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZAT