<HEAD>Quayle Discusses Soviet Crackdown with Dissident Editor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> stretched a 20-minute appointment Thursday with the editor of a dissident Soviet journal into a one-hour, 10-minute discussion of ethnic violence in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, a spokesman said. <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON>, editor of the unofficial magazine `` Glasnost'' later told a news conference that he had discussed with <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> the killing of 22 Soviet Georgians in the city of <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION> on April 9. <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> said he believed the killings had been orchestrated by the Kremlin to provide a pretext for cracking down on democratic movements in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, especially those in the non-Russian republics. The killings, however, provoked an outcry in the Soviet parliament and there has been no nation-wide crackdown. <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> version of events differed sharply from official accounts. A commission of the Soviet parliament is investigating the <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION> incident. <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON>, who has been in and out of jail since Soviet Communist Party General Secretary <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> rose to power in March 1985, called the Soviet leader `` a hell of a criminal.'' A spokesman for <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said the vice president `` really enjoyed taking to this guy.'' `` He found him a fascinating and courageous man,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckwith </PERSON>. The spokesman declined to offer a judgment on <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> views, but said that extending the meeting by 50 minutes was unusual and `` it disrupted the vice president's afternoon schedule.''
