<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The British <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> correspondent and his two-man camera crew were assaulted and interrogated by Chinese police, the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. Correspondent <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> and the crew were filming civilians next to a burned-out tank Wednesday night when six gun-wielding secret policemen and several uniformed policemen set on them, the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We ran into trouble while ignoring the martial law decree banning all foreign television coverage of the unrest,'' <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> said on <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> TV. `` All media coverage here is theoretically illegal. As we filmed civilians beside a burned-out tank, we were assaulted by half a dozen police brandishing loaded pistols.'' <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> said half the crew's equipment was `` deliberately smashed.'' `` Then at gunpoint we were forced to kneel in the road for two tense minutes. A pistol was put to the temple of our sound recordist <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Moss </PERSON>. After that, we were frog-marched with our hands up past a silent crowd of civilians.'' <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> said he was `` kicked and cussed'' on the march to a factory complex where they were detained for another 30 minutes before being ordered at gunpoint to leave. Their remaining equipment and videotape was confiscated, he said.
