<HEAD>Whittle Plans To Take Channel One Service National Next Spring</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf, `But neither..., with 2 grafs to include
reference to C-Span service. Picks up last graf. A longer version moved
on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The advertiser-supported Channel One news service for teens will be offered to schools nationwide starting in March 1990, packaged with two new educational networks, the creator of the service said Thursday. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Whittle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>, said his company expects to spend $ 200 million on startup costs involved in giving 8,000 or more schools the video equipment needed to receive Channel One programming. He plans to pay for it with $ 85 million to $ 100 million each year from advertisers who pay to pitch products on Channel One's daily news show. Critics ncluding national educational groups argue that advertisers should not be allowed to pitch their wares to youngsters in the classroom. `` We have listened to our critics,'' <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON> told a news conference in announcing the national launch of Channel One. But he said their main complaint about advertising was `` unaddressable.'' He said if schools are going to get both a daily news show and the equipment to show it `` you have to pay for it'' and that advertising is the most feasible way because the federal governmment and corporate philanthropy have not provided the money. Nonetheless, <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON> said, he has modified the Channel One service that was tested for five weeks this past spring at six schools across the country and featured ads for jeans, shampoo, chewing gum, candy bars and acne medicine. Whittle said schools signing up for Channel One can have some rather than all of their classrooms wired to receive the program and need not show it to the whole school. However, he said schools that participate still will be obliged to show the program every day in those classrooms that have the Channel One equipment. In addition to Channel One, <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON> will donate five hours of satellite time every school day for a channel called the Classroom Channel that would carry non-commercial educational programming. The Classroom Channel would be run by a board independent of Whittle Communcations. <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON> said it was likely the board would decide against allowing advertising on that service. Schools could pick and choose what they want to use from that channel, he said. He said <ORGANIZATION> Whittle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> would donate $ 500,000 a year for the board to acquire rights to programming for the Classroom Channel. The programs would include public broadcasting documentaries and instructional shows such as an advanced algebra class or language lesson. <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON> said he also was developing a third network, the Educators Channel, to carry programming for educators, such as briefings by national education groups. Schools participating in Channel One would be given equipment to receive all three channels in exchange for running the Channel One program every day. <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Charren </PERSON>, who heads a national children's advocacy group, said she was unswayed by <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON>'s modifications. `` It's the same deal with better packaging,'' she said. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Marx </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administratrors </ORGANIZATION> said, `` It still turns the classroom into a marketplace for products rather than a marketplace for ideas.'' Whittle hopes to make Channel One available in 1,000 middle and high schools in March 1990 and add schools at a rate of 500 or more a month, giving each school video equipment worth $ 40,000 to $ 50,000. Competition has sprung up since Whittle tested Channel One. <ORGANIZATION> Turner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> plans to begin a daily ad-free news program for schools starting in August, while the Discovery Channel cable network says it intends to make commercial-free documentary programming. C-Span, the <ORGANIZATION> Cable-Satellite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> that provides coverage of congressional proceedings, has been providing programming for use in the classroom since 1986 and said 3,400 teachers already use it. <PERSON> C-Span </PERSON> is expanding that service starting in late August. But no cable network is donating equipment to the schools on the scale Whittle has envisioned. Whittle released survey results Wednesday indicating students who watched Channel One were better informed about daily events than their counterparts who did not watch it. The surveys also claim a majority of teachers, students and administrators find the commercials an acceptable price to pay for the program.
