<HEAD>Study Says CDC Significantly Underestimates AIDS Cases</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 6-8: ``President Bush,'' with Bush comments from
news conference.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> study released Thursday suggests that federal officials may be significantly underestimating the number of Americans with AIDS and that there are more whites and fewer blacks with the disease than previously believed. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Laumann </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> said that estimates by the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> of the numbers of AIDS case are distorted because affluent whites can afford to be treated discreetly by physicians who do not report the disease. He said in a telephone interview that there also are cases that are not reported due to bureaucratic problems that slow the count or misfile cases. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> makes its estimate based on cases reported to official agencies. An undercount or a failure to report cases could seriously affect the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> estimate, said <PERSON> Laumann </PERSON>. `` We are contending that there is an undercount, but we do n't know the scale of it,'' said <PERSON> Laumann </PERSON>, who co-authored a report appearing Friday in the journal Science `` We can estimate the demographic composition, but not the gross numbers themselves. The reason we're being cautious is that this is too small a sample.'' President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, questioned about the need for mandatory reporting of new AIDS cases, said he would not favor any type of reporting that would jeopardize the patient's right to privacy. `` There's a lot of suffering, a lot of human tragedy out there,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, adding that anything less than `` absolutely discreet handling'' would not be helpful in fighting the AIDS epidemic. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, answering questions at a televised news conference Thursday night, said that people should be encouraged to talk to their doctors frankly about AIDS. To gather data for the AIDS study, <PERSON> Laumann </PERSON> and his associates conducted interviews of 1,481 households around the country. The households were selected to reflect a cross section of the population. Each respondent was asked if he knew an acquaintance who had AIDS. To validate the accuracy of the answers, the respondents also were asked if they had an acquaintance who had been murdered. Earlier studies had proven that response to the homicide survey accurately reflected the actual number of murders. This suggested that answers to the AIDS question would be equally accurate. The results, said the study, `` suggest that the white proportion -LRB- of AIDS cases -RRB- is substantially higher than <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> reports and that a substantially greater share of the cases is in the midwestern region.'' According to <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> figures from March 7, whites compose about 60 percent of the nation's AIDS cases. The <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> study said the correct number is 72 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said that 26 percent of all cases are black and 14 percent are Hispanic. The <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> results estimate these totals as 18 percent for blacks, and 6 percent for Hispanics. Cases in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>, make up only 8 percent of the national total. The <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> study said that <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> cases actually compose 20 percent of the national total. The comparative figures for other regions: _ East <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>, 39 percent of the national total; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, 19 percent. _ South <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>, 26 percent; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, 25 percent. _ West <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>, 27 percent; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, 36 percent. <PERSON> Laumann </PERSON> said that `` logic alone'' suggested something wrong with the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> figures for the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, he said, `` has all of the AIDS risk factors,'' such as a population of injection drug users, and yet the city was said to have only 3.1 cases of AIDS per 10,000 residents, compared to a national total of 3.7 cases per 10,000. Also, he said, according to the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> figures, `` <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> at the time of the 1988 survey had an absolute number of AIDS cases that was equal to or even exceeded that of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. And <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> has 38 percent of the population of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Laumann </PERSON> said that <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> also has big cities where the AIDS risk factors are common. `` That just does n't make sense,'' he said. <PERSON> Laumann </PERSON> submitted the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> study to officials at the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> for comment, and he said `` these results do n't surprise them.'' `` They know that sexually transmitted diseases are generally undercounted for the white population because people go to personal physicians and one of their things they are doing is buying some discretion about it,'' he said. He said cases were undercounted in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> because of a flawed system of data collection by official agencies, noting `` there's been a scandal for sometime about the AIDS office in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and how inadequate it was.'' <PERSON> Gayle </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON>, a spokesperson for the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, said there were no officials available to comment on the new study. AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is fatal disease caused by a virus that is spread most frequently by sexual intercourse or by the sharing of needles among intravenous drug users. Through the month of April, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> reports that AIDS had been diagnosed in 94,280 Americans, of whom more than half, or 53,544, have died since June 1, 1981. No one is known to have recovered from AIDS. Science, which reported the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> study, is the journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Science.
