<FIRST>a a PM-ElksRacism Adv13   06-08 1135</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elks Racism, Adv 13,1162</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Tues PMs, June 13, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Elks Facing Challenges To All-Male, Virtually All-White Membership</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For more than a century, the <ORGANIZATION> Elks </ORGANIZATION> club has chosen the kind of members it believes stand for the American ideals of equality, charity and brotherhood. For all that time, almost all of them have been white men. Even in cities as racially diverse as <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, Elks lodges remain the preserve of the white male, with written rules that ban women and voting procedures that critics say stack the deck against blacks. But that may be changing, according to civil libertarians and legal experts, because of recent challenges to the membership practices of the 121-year-old Benevolent and Protective Order of Elks. Several <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> lodges have threatened to go to court if they are unsuccessful in persuading the national organization at its convention next month in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> to change voting rules to admit more black members. The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> attorney general's office is investigating possible civil rights violations by a <LOCATION> Lompoc </LOCATION> lodge that rejected two black applicants. And a <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> woman rejected for membership in a <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> George </LOCATION> lodge has filed a sex discrimination lawsuit against the Elks club. Elks leaders have strongly defended the club against all challenges, contending that members have a constitutional right to associate with whomever they choose. But legal experts say that the Elks will be held to the same civil rights laws the courts have applied to the Rotary club and other organizations. Ultimately, they say, the <ORGANIZATION> Elks </ORGANIZATION> will be forced to change their ways. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has been very clear that it is not at all solicitous and protective of groups that want to discriminate,'' said <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Chemerinsky </PERSON>, law professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> and an expert on civil rights litigation. `` I'm sure that would include the Elks.'' The accusations of racism and sexism and the prospect of change in membership have rattled Elks leaders and tarnished the reputation of the 1.6 million-member group. `` Why's everybody picking on the Elks?'' asks spokesman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Yothers </PERSON>. `` I wish somebody would tell the true story, the good side of the Elks club.'' The Elks project an image as <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> as the flag, its members donating their time and money to everything from rodeos to pancake breakfasts. The club raised $ 53 million last year for charity nationally. Critics say the true story is actually an unusual mixture of charity and discrimination. For most of its history, the Elks explicitly limited membership to white men. In 1973, the bylaws were changed to include all men, but women still were banned and voting rules that gave great power to a small group of members has effectively kept out blacks. In the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> area, for example, the 13 Elks lodges have more than 9,000 members, none of them women, none of them black, and only a smattering of them Asian and Hispanic, according to lodge officials, most of whom spoke on condition of anonymity. One lodge exalted ruler said he was unaware of the change in rules to allow black members. His lodge has never had one. Critics find it ironic that lodge members who are willing to raise money for charitable groups serving black children are unwilling to share a drink in the lodge with a black businessman. College-bound girls are given Elks scholarships, but college-educated women ca n't join the lodge. `` It just makes you feel a little disappointed that this sort of thing could be happening in this day and age,'' said <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutchinson </PERSON>, 57, a <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> housing official who was one of the two blacks rejected this year by the lodge in <LOCATION> Lompoc </LOCATION>, 140 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The other was <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, 56, a Realtor. The two have been told that fewer than a dozen lodge members cast `` no'' votes by placing black marbles into the voting box. Even though nearly 140 members supported them, Elks voting rules require only three black marbles to reject, or blackball, an applicant. `` I truly felt deep down in my heart that they would accept me,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>. `` But it is just a few bad apples. I feel more pity for those people than anger at my situation.'' The rejection of <PERSON> Hutchinson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, two longtime residents with many friends in the community and lodge, outraged the city of 31,000. The newspaper printed angry editorials, the school board refused to accept <ORGANIZATION> Elks </ORGANIZATION> scholarships, and a boycott of Elks functions was in the works. Just last week, the <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barbara </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> voted to block donations from a local lodge, part of <LOCATION> Lompoc </LOCATION>'s region, to city-sponsored youth programs In late March, Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Verdugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> confirmed that the state was investigating the lodge for possible violations of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s civil rights law, the same law the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld in ordering the Rotary club to admit women. Under community pressure, the <LOCATION> Lompoc </LOCATION> lodge and others in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barbara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> passed a resolution to urge the national Grand Lodge to change voting procedures to a two-thirds majority. If the national organization balks, the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> lodges plan to go to court with the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>. `` Sure we're concerned'' about opposing the Grand Lodge, said <PERSON> Butch </PERSON> <PERSON> Simas </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Elks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> leader. `` But we are willing to go against the national lodge.'' While the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> lodges prepare to challenge the voting rules, <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Beynon </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, continues to battle her local lodge, with a lot less fanfare, for the right to become a member. Ms. <PERSON> Beynon </PERSON>, a construction company manager denied membership in 1987, contends the <ORGANIZATION> Elks </ORGANIZATION> club is violating state liquor laws banning discrimination in most places that serve alcoholic beverages by the glass. Her suit is pending. `` The local Elks lodge in this state is one of few places where people can conduct business over a cocktail at lunch or a drink after work,'' said her attorney, <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON>. `` By excluding women, the <ORGANIZATION> Elks </ORGANIZATION> have denied a large segment of society of the right to develop business contacts.'' The challenges to the Elks membership practices in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> have rankled national Elks leaders. <PERSON> Yothers </PERSON> denies that racism was at work in <LOCATION> Lompoc </LOCATION>, noting that no member of that lodge has admitted blackballing the two black applicants because of their race. However, he acknowledged that if they did make such an admission they would face expulsion from the lodge. He also said it was illogical to admit women to the <ORGANIZATION> Elks </ORGANIZATION> club, which he calls a fraternal organization similar to a college fraternity. `` You do n't let women in fraternities, and you do n't let males in sororities. This whole thing just does n't make sense.''
