<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-StevenBanks Adv09   06-08 0793</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Steven Banks, Adv 09,0809</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday PMs, June 9, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Steven Banks Brings Innovative One-Man Show to Showtime</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Banks </PERSON> is not easy to categorize. He's a comedian, actor, rock musician and impressionist. He's very funny _ and he has something to say. His one-man tour-de-force, `` <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Banks </PERSON>' Home Entertainment Center,'' has been packing them in on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, and viewers of the Showtime cable network get a look-see beginning Saturday. The hour-long show was taped on stage at Marines Memorial Theatre in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. This month, Banks begins an extended run at the <ORGANIZATION> Canon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theatre </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>. Set in Banks' slovenly bachelor pad, the show is a series of imaginative comic vignettes, but in a larger sense it's an inspiring story about being stuck in life at thirtysomething and taking a risk to get your dream. It opens with Banks coming home early from his dead-end job in the corporate maze and donning his jammies so he can delve into his fantasy life as a rock star. He cheers his own entrance with the chant: `` Banks! Banks! Banks! Banks! ...'' His telephone messages include repeated and increasingly irritated calls from the office, but also a surprise call from <PERSON> Lance </PERSON>, a high-school pal who's now a rock star. The eccentric Banks' kitchen shelves are lined with boxes of <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hines </PERSON> cookie mix, the sink is full of dirty dishes, and the walls plastered with posters of his musical heroes. The slightest task, be it talking on the phone or typing, turns into a performance. Banks is being hounded by his boss, Mr. <PERSON> Buttle </PERSON>, to finish writing a speech that was due that afternoon. Though his intentions are good, Banks constantly distracts himself by any means available to avoid the mundane, and grown-up, job. At one point, he emerges from his closet in a tacky Vegas jumpsuit, stuffs it with a pillow and launches into a homage to <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON>, `` Who Killed the <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rock </ORGANIZATION>' n' Roll?'' Banks' childlike imaginings turn bitingly satiric. `` It was n't me, says <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Marie </PERSON>,'' goes one verse. `` I loved my dad and he loved me. ... When I get all of his mon-ey, I'll give it to Scientology. ...'' Banks is also being pressured by his girlfriend, <PERSON> Phoebe </PERSON>, who intends to move in with him. Not only that, the landlord is complaining about the noise from his drums and promises to toss Banks out if there is one more drumbeat from his apartment. So Banks grabs up a guitar and gets so involved in his impersonation of <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON>, he answers the phone in a nasal, `` There's no one here by that name. This is the <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON> residence. ... D-Y-L-A-N. ... <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> ... B-O-B. ... Yes, it is. ... Why, thank you very much!'' When <PERSON> Lance </PERSON> calls back, <PERSON> Banks </PERSON> thinks he's being offered the chance of a lifetime _ Lance's drummer has quit. But Banks' drum audition over the phone only succeeds in costing him his apartment _ he's already lost his girlfriend and is on the verge of losing his job So he does the only reasonable thing _ explodes into a punk-rock ode to his own life: `` Twenty-two: degree! Twenty-three: McDonald's! Twenty-four: Unemployment! Twenty-five: <PERSON> Buttle </PERSON>! Twenty-six: <PERSON> Buttle </PERSON>! Twenty-seven, 28, 29, 30, 31, 32! But now I'm 33, I'm tryin' to be cool, I'm jumping around in my living room ...'' The song fades as Banks realizes that's exactly what he's doing and his life is a shambles But this is a show with a happy ending, even in real life. The theater audience gives Banks a standing ovation and provides an authentic, `` Banks! Banks! Banks!''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: AT <LOCATION> HOME </LOCATION> <LOCATION> WITH </LOCATION> <LOCATION> MARTIN </LOCATION> <LOCATION> SCORSESE </LOCATION> _ `` Italianamerican,'' an early <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON> work, in which the director of `` Taxi Driver'' and `` The Last Temptation of Christ'' interviewed his Italian parents, airs Sunday on The Learning Channel as part of the series `` Coming to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' While he was a film-school student, <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON> asked his mother to let him film her making her spaghetti sauce. He he ended up with a touching and intimate reminiscence of what it was like to grow up the children of immigrants in a new land. The interviews are intercut with still photos of <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>'s grandparents and archival footage of lower <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. ... ` MOLLY' RE-UPS _ The Lifetime cable network has ordered 26 more episodes of `` The Days and Nights of <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>.'' The series, starring <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, was canceled last year by <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, but picked up by the cable channel for 13 new episodes that began airing in April. The 26 newest episodes will begin appearing in early 1990.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, June 9</NOTE>
