<SECOND>PM-Saudi-Oil Strike,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Saudi Aramco Confirms Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAHRAN, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aramco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s oil-producing firm, says it struck a large well that could yield 8,000 barrels a day of crude oil The company, which operates the world's largest oil field in a country with the world's largest reserves, said Wednesday the find was made in the <LOCATION> Hawtah </LOCATION> region in central <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> about 120 miles south of the capital <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION>. Saudi Aramco said preliminary tests indicated the well could yield 8,000 barrels a day of light crude containing only 0.06 percent sulphur. Sadad, <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Husseini </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Saudi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aramco </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for exploration and production, said the find `` confirms the potential for substantial discoveries ... in rock formations recently studied by <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aramco </LOCATION> and assessed to be highly prospective.'' Oil industry executives and company sources reported the strike Tuesday. But they said it was made in the nearby <LOCATION> Khurais </LOCATION> region and gave no details. The find was made as part of a major exploration program launched by <ORGANIZATION> Saudi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aramco </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 after the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> government expanded the company's exploration concession. It was the first strike since <ORGANIZATION> Aramco </ORGANIZATION> was restructured in late 1988 and the first in a promising area only recently identifed. Most of the company's oil field is located in the east part of the country. Saudi Aramco announced earlier this year that its proven reserves have gone up from 169 billion to 252 billion barrels, and could reach 315 billion barrels. The company has discovered 52 oil fields and one commercial gas field since it started exploration 55 years ago. Under its current Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries quota, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> exports 4.524 million barrels a day, but in the oil boom years output peaked at more than 11 million barrels a day.
