<HEAD>New Season Production Outlook Better Than Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New season world grain production may be larger than forecast, with early signs of an 11.4 percent increase on the current season's drought-hit yield, according to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. The council, one of the foremost grain forecasting bodies, now puts world wheat output between July 1989 to June 1990 at 533 million metric tons, compared with 537 million forecast last month and 504 million last season. Production of coarse grains _ principally maize, rye, oats, barley and sorghum, is now forecast at 840 million tons, against 830 million previously and 728 million this season, the council said Wednesday. The rise is attributed to improved prospects for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, with forecasts of 112 million tons for the Soviets, up from with 97.6 million in 1988-89, and 240 million for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, compared with 149.6 million. Bigger coarse grain crops are also foreseen for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> at 95 million against 93.6 million this season and the European Community at 90 million, compared with 89.3 million. The Indian harvest, however, is expected to fall 2.6 million tons to 30 million. Forecasts of 1989-90 wheat production, with 1988-89 estimates in brackets, include: <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> 90.0 million -LRB- 84.5 million -RRB-; <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> 89 million -LRB- 87 million -RRB-; the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> 86.7 million -LRB- 85.3 million -RRB-; the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> 56.5 million -LRB- 49.3 million -RRB-; and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> 50 million -LRB- 45.1 million -RRB-. The council's first forecast of 1989-90 world coarse grain trade is down eight million tons at 93 million, reflecting the prospect of lower Soviet imports, which could drop by 9 million to 16 million.
