<HEAD>Synopsis of Two Deals Facing Time Shareholders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Time-Paramount, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> shareholders are faced with two deals involving their publishing and cable company _ a merger with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and a tender offer from <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Here is a capsule description on what is being proposed:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>THE WARNER DEAL:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> have agreed on a merger that involves an exchange of stock to create a company that would be the world's largest media and entertainment concern. Under that plan, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> shareholders would get one share in the new company for each share of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> stock they own. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> shareholders would get 0.465 shares of stock in the new company for each <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> share they hold. The arrangement would leave <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> shareholders with roughly 40 percent of the new company and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> shareholders with the rest.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>THE PARAMOUNT DEAL:</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Paramount has launched a tender offer of $ 175 a share for all of Time's stock. The offer expires at midnight July 5 unless extended. Under this plan, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> shareholders will get $ 175 in cash for each share of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s stock they hold, providing that at least a majority of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s shares are tendered and other conditions are met.
</TEXT>
