<HEAD>Paramount Bid For Time Inc. Boosts Other Media Stocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Time-Paramount, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Media and entertainment companies were in the spotlight on Wall Street as news of <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 10.7 billion bid for <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> revived speculation about possible bids for other communications concerns The stocks of several big media firms rose sharply Wednesday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> rose $ 1.87 -LCB- to close at $ 56.62 -LCB-; <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> surged $ 4.75 to $ 205.62 -LCB-; <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities-ABC </ORGANIZATION> picked up $ 7.50 to $ 468; and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, whose planned merger with Time was cast into doubt by the Paramount bid, rose $ 1.75 to $ 53.50. Wednesday's advances were similar to gains chalked up earlier this year when Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> announced plans to merge and form the world's largest media concern. News of a big takeover bid for a company often sparks interest in other firms in that industry, but the activity in media and entertainment stocks has had an added twist recently. The media, information and entertainment industries have undergone a wave of consolidations in recent years, with large companies snapping up other firms to create media giants. The buyers mainly have been foreign publishing and broadcasting giants such as <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Maxwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and electronics behemoth <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. These companies have scooped up <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> media concerns in a torrent of deals made possible in recent years by their own wealth and the weak <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar. The growth of media conglomerates was uppermost in the minds of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> executives as they negotiated their agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman, apparently wants to be part of the trend. If he succeeds in acquiring Time, his own entertainment and publishing conglomerate would have a projected $ 7 billion in sales. A <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> combination would have projected revenue of more than $ 10 billion. Paramount, which changed its name from <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> on Monday, owns <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Simon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Schuster and Prentice Hall publishers, and a number of other broadcasting, entertainment and publishing businesses. Time publishes magazines _ including Time, <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> and Sports Illustrated _ and books and also owns broadcast and cable television properties including Home Box Office.
