<HEAD>Court Denies Eastern's Appeal on Pilots' Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURAN NEERGAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> says a federal appeals court ruling means <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' attempt to expand its limited service may be stalled. But <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON> declined to comment on how the ruling Wednesday by the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> would affect plans for Eastern's reorganization. A three-judge panel of the appeals court upheld a lower court ruling denying <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s request for an injunction against the pilots union to stop the strike. <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON> said the Miami-based airline has no plans to appeal the case further. In another setback for Eastern, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it plans to file an antitrust suit blocking <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed sale to <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of its airport gates in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and its <LOCATION> Philadelphia-Toronto </LOCATION> route The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the $ 85 million proposal `` threatens to lessen competition'' in airline service between <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and other cities, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Boudin </PERSON>, acting antitrust chief for the department. The appeals court ruling was prompted by a lawsuit Eastern filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> after most of the airline's 3,600 pilots honored picket lines set up by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union when it went on strike March 4. The walkout, also supported by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> flight attendants, virtually grounded the carrier and compelled it to seek bankruptcy protection from creditors March 9. <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, a communications specialist with the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the ruling `` reaffirms the pilots' solidarity in dealing with -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman -RRB- <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> He also said the ruling strengthens the union's backing of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> commodities trader <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON>, who is trying to buy the carrier from <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s parent company. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said that in light of the ruling, officials for <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON> will meet with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankruptcy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to discuss the proposed buyout again. Eastern's creditors have rejected <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON>'s proposal. <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilian </PERSON>, a striking <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilot in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, said the ruling was not a surprise but was a morale booster. `` As time moves along, we get more and more little victories,'' he said. `` This is a good victory at a good time. It gives us that much more resolve and enthusiasm.'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said the ruling means <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> will not have enough pilots to carry through <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s plan to rebuild the airline as a smaller carrier and sell about $ 1.8 billion of its assets. Eastern said Wednesday it is negotiating to sell its <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> routes, possibly to rival <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. `` We have talked to American,'' <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON> said from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. He said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> also has held talks on the routes with other airlines. <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON> declined to identify the other carriers interested in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> network, which served 10 cities before Eastern was struck, or to disclose <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s asking price. Wall Street analysts have estimated the value of the network at about $ 150 million. Any sale of Eastern assets must be approved by a federal bankruptcy court judge in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The judge recently approved the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s Northeast shuttle to developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> for $ 365 million. American spokesman <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> acknowledged American's general interest in <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> assets but would not confirm that talks had been held on the South American routes. `` We're looking at things that might be for sale,'' <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said from <LOCATION> American </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, headquarters. For American, the nation's largest airline, the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> routes would bolster its strategy to expand overseas. American recently added new flights to <LOCATION