<HEAD>Lawmaker Warns FAA Chief on Eastern Maintenance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shortages of staff and spare parts could be hampering strikebound <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' ability to properly maintain its fleet, the head of a congressional panel has told the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Rep. <PERSON> Cardiss </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, D-Ill., chairwoman of the Government Activities and <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> of the House Committee on Government Operations, expressed the concern in a letter to acting <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittington </PERSON> While it is clear Eastern has suffered staffing problems because of the 3-month-old walkout by <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union members, pilots and flight attendants, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>' letter raised the question of whether the few planes still flying are receiving proper care. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> recently concluded a special investigation of maintenance at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s facilities at its <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> base and at <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, but has not disclosed its findings. The transportation subcommittee's staff has reviewed internal company documents indicating that `` manpower and parts shortages continue to plague the maintenance function of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> wrote the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> chief last Thursday. A copy of the letter was obtained by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The impact of maintenance on airline safety has been highlighted by several accidents. In one case, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> largely blamed <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' maintenance program for failing to detect fatigue damage to the fuselage of a 19-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 that split open over <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, killing a flight attendant. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s maintenance shortcomings appear to persist despite several <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> investigations of the carrier and `` substantial'' fines against the airline, as well as commitments by management to correct the problems. <PERSON> Whittington </PERSON> has n't yet responded to <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>' letter, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said Wednesday. He said the special investigation was completed on May 12 but the report on it has n't yet been submitted to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> chief `` Everything they -LRB- Eastern -RRB- do is being watched,'' <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said. `` We're going to keep a very close eye on Eastern until the strike is over.'' Eastern spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON> said he could n't comment on <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>' letter because he was n't familiar with the documents to which she referred. `` Eastern is under the most intensive scrutiny that any airline's ever been subjected to,'' he said, adding that the adequacy of its manpower and parts could easily be checked Early last month, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> temporarily surrendered its repair station certificate at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> John </LOCATION> <LOCATION> F. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> after the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> determined the carrier had failed to follow its system for recording and inspecting maintenance work. The suspension was for actions that predated the March 4 start of the strike, which pushed <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> into bankruptcy court five days later. Soon after the JFK certificate was pulled, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> sent nine inspectors to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s main base in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> to determine if violations of maintenance record-keeping rules, such as those found in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, existed in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. JFK, <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hartsfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> are the sites of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s three principal maintenance facilities. If the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> ordered <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> to temporarily relinquish its certificates for the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> facilities, that could severely hamper the airline's ability to operate. When a maintenance certificate is suspended, the airline is prohibited from doing work at the facility until deficiencies are corrected. The work must be contracted out, or planes needing repairs must be ferried elsewhere. In her letter, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> called <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s surrendering of its JFK certificate `` unprecedented.'' `` I am concerned that this may not be an isolated case, and may be in fact, an indication of systemic problems throughout <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s maintenance department,'' the lawmaker told <PERSON> Whittington </PERSON> She asked him to advise her of the results of the latest investigation as soon as possible. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>' subcommittee previously held hearings on maintenance practices at Eastern and their potential impact on passenger safety. She has expressed concern about <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to continue some operations during the strike. The airline has faced a number of <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> investigations in recent years, including one in 1986 that resulted in a $ 9.5 million fine for safety infractions and a threatened suspension of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s overall operating license Eastern's unions contend the maintenance problems are systemwide and endanger safety. They accuse supervisors of `` pencil-whipping,'' or signing their names to documents on aircraft repairs that were n't made The unions also charge that management, in an effort to cut costs and maintain flying schedules, has bullied mechanics and pilots who complain about serious maintenance violations. Eastern countercharges that some machinists hid or destroyed maintenance records at <LOCATION> JFK </LOCATION> and then told the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> that company supervisors neglected to have necessary work performed. Company representatives discovered records hidden in file cabinets and stuffed under sofa cushions in union areas at the airport, said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON>. `` We've never dispatched an unsafe plane; we have one of the best safety records in the industry,'' <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said. He called union complaints `` a deliberate attempt to drive away our passengers and weaken the company.''
