<FIRST>r f PM-Fed-Currency Bjt   06-08 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed-Currency, Bjt,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Central Bank Reveals Active Dollar-Selling Last Winter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> spent more than $ 2 billion to temper the dollar's rise in foreign exchange last winter, as higher interest rates and political uncertainty abroad bolstered the value of the currency, a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> report shows. The latest quarterly foreign-exchange report issued Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> showed the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 2.14 billion for the equivalent West German marks and Japanese yen during the three months ended April 30. The dollar sales, which were mostly for marks, were the largest since the $ 2.93 billion sold during the May-July 1988 period, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> said. In the previous November-January quarter, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> bought $ 2.4 billion against the mark and yen, then sold $ 1.88 billion against marks as market sentiment turned more bullish for the dollar. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Y </PERSON>. Cross, an executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, said the latest operations were designed to maintain market stability and generally were coordinated with the central banks of the `` Group of Seven'' industrial nations. Besides the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> G-7 </ORGANIZATION> includes <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Cross said that some of the government's intervention operations were done jointly with other central banks, but at other times the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> acted alone after notifying its trading partners. Currency traders are often keenly aware of the activities of central banks in the open markets, but the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s policy is to comment only well after the fact. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> also does not provide any data on intervention by foreign central banks. The government's dollar-selling operations during the February-April period came amid strong foreign demand for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> short-term interest rates were comparatively higher than those abroad as a result of inflation-fighting efforts by the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>. That made dollar-denominated assets more attractive to foreigners, thereby increasing the need to convert to dollars. Political developments abroad also weighed against several major foreign currencies. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, an insider-trading scandal brought the government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> under increasing pressure, while in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the imposition and subsequent removal of a controversial withholding tax on interest income brought considerable confusion to the market. Intervention involving marks took place from Feb. 2 to Feb. 6, when the government sold $ 350 million, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> report. The government also entered the market between March 8 and March 30, when it sold $ 1.419 billion; on April 10 and April 11, when it sold $ 170 million; and on April 30, when it sold $ 50 million, the report said. Sales of dollars for yen were made during the March 8-30 period, amounting to $ 100 million, and on April 30, amounting to $ 50 million, it said. During the February-April period the dollar reached a high of 1.9025 marks and 133.50 yen. The dollar has risen even further lately, trading around 1.98 marks and 142 yen. The dollar reached its highest point of the decade in February 1985. It declined slightly until September 1985, when <ORGANIZATION> G-7 </ORGANIZATION> leaders agreed to lower its value to help narrow the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade gap and stave off protectionist sentiment in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar touched bottom in the final days of 1987 before rebounding sharply at the beginning of 1988.
