<FIRST>r f PM-Rostenkowski-CapitalGains     06-08 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rostenkowski-Capital Gains,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appears Willingness to Compromise on Capital Gains Tax Reduction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said he would consider accepting lower capital gains tax rates as a revenue-raising measure. `` I have n't seen a way'' to raise revenue in the next fiscal year without a capital gains rate cut, Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> in an interview published today He said that with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s opposition to new taxes, `` The only thing that seems negotiable is capital gains.'' <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> has long opposed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal to reduce the capital gains rate _ currently the same as the income tax rate on ordinary income _ to 15 percent. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, a committee aide who spoke on condition of anonymity said Wednesday night that <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> had not changed his opposition to a reduction. But in an interview published today in The Wall Street Journal, <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> said: `` Let the process begin. ... Everything is on the table.'' <PERSON> Rostenskowski </PERSON> recognizes that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who campaigned on a slogan of `` read my lips _ no new taxes,'' and a majority of committee Republicans are going to have to accept any revenue compromise, the aide said. `` Proponents of capital gains reduction have a real leg up'' in such a situation, the aide said, because of the recognition on all sides that any change, up or down, in capital gains rates yields a revenue increase in the first year. Capital gains are the increases in value of any assets, such as stocks. A tax rate increase captures a bigger slice of the proceeds of asset sales that would be made in any case; a rate decrease stimulates more sales and brings in more government revenue that way. Economists disagree over what happens after the first year. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> argues that there are permanently more transactions with lower rates than they would otherwise be; <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> and others argue that this is not so and people selling stock would get an unjustified tax break. Additionally, opponents of lower rates say that stock trading is done by people of high incomes and benefits of those rates are not available to those living on modest salaries. The <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is under instructions from the <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to come up with an additional $ 5.3 billion in revenue for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1. The <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taxation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> estimated that a cut in rates to 15 percent as proposed by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would yield $ 3.5 billion in the first year though it would reduce revenue after that; the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> estimated the first-year gain at $ 4.2 billion. Though often in recent years capital gains have been taxed a separately stated rates, currently gains are treated like all other income. The top current federal income tax rate is 33 percent.
