<FIRST>r f PM-AutoRecalls     06-08 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Recalls,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Car of the Year' Among Some Recalled T'birds and Cougars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Potential brake or rear suspension problems prompted <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to recall about 119,000 of its Mercury Cougar and Ford Thunderbird cars, including the winner of a magazine's prestigious `` Car of the Year'' award. In announcing the recall Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said it knew of no accidents or injuries because of the problems. Spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Parris </PERSON> said all of the cars were assembled at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s plant in <LOCATION> Lorain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, between October 1988 and March 1989. Between 5 percent and 10 percent of them were Thunderbird Super Coupes. Of all those recalled, about 11,250 Thunderbirds and <ORGANIZATION> Cougars </ORGANIZATION> also will be checked for a part which, if left in place for a number of miles, could cause the rear suspension to fall apart. Motor Trend magazine gave its `` Car of the Year'' award to the Thunderbird SC in January. The car has had other problems since its formal introduction in December 1988, but Wednesday's action was the first recall involving the Super Coupe. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said that during a full turn at less than 5 mph, part of the front suspension of all the <ORGANIZATION> Cougars </ORGANIZATION> and Thunderbirds made during the five-month period could hit part of the brake mechanism. That would cause an increase in pedal travel the next time the brakes were applied, decreasing effectiveness. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said the problem could be repeated during the next low-speed, full-turn brake application. Also involved in recall were about 11,250 Thunderbirds and Cougars made in mid-January. The company said 133 rear-suspension knuckles were heated improperly by a supplier, which could result in cracks and failure of the suspension. It was n't clear how many cars received knuckles from the bad batch, <PERSON> Parris </PERSON> said. A suspension knuckle is an arm that attaches the wheel assembly to the frame. The company said it was unaware of any injuries or accidents because of either problem. Inspections and repairs will be performed free, the company said. The Thunderbird SC, which stands for Super Coupe, has had other problems since production began last year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> withheld dealer deliveries of many of the cars late last year and early this year so it could replace a cast-iron crankshaft with a forged one. Crankshafts change the up-and-down motion of the pistons to rotary motion that goes to wheels. The crankshafts were replaced in the Super Coupe and the Cougar XR7. In February, the company said it had completed replacing an engine mounting bolt in about 10,600 of all versions of the Thunderbird and Cougar which never got to dealers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
