<HEAD>McCaw Begins Tender Offer For LIN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 new grafs to UPDATE with tender offer beginning;
uppicks 5th graf pvs: ``We certainly ...; edits to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cellular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> today began its $ 5.85 billion tender offer for the shares of <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> it does not already own. The $ 120 a share offer, which will expire on July 6 unless extended, requires among other conditions approval from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. In a news release, <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> stated such approval could take six months. Shares of both companies edged lower in early trading today, <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION> was down $ 1.75 to $ 127.75 a share and <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> dipped 75 cents to $ 46.25 in national over-the-counter trading. On Wednesday, a day after <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> announced its bid for the New York-based cellular phone, television and publishing company, <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION> stock soared $ 26 a share to $ 129.50 in over-the-counter trading and <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> stock rose $ 3.75 to $ 47 a share. But the bid had a broad spinoff effect on the stock prices of other companies involved in the cellular telephone business. Officials at rival companies said the bid created a new benchmark for the value of their cellular properties. `` We certainly see this as an important announcement,'' said <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Olberg </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telesis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telesis </ORGANIZATION> rose $ 1.12 -LCB- to $ 42 and <ORGANIZATION> Southwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> rose $ 1 to $ 53.87 -LCB-. Cellular operations are a small part of those companies' revenue. By acquiring <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> would have twice the potential cellular market of <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Telesis </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Southwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, its closest competitors. Combining both sets of franchises would form the `` regional supersystem'' of cellular holdings that <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> has been seeking, said analyst <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Argus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Cellular franchises have grown in popularity with improvements in technology and customer demand for mobile phones. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said a battle for LIN's stock was likely. `` The market is obviously anticipating a bidding war erupting,'' he said. Spokespersons for <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Telesis </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Southwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> refused to comment on whether their companies are interested in LIN, although analysts have cited both as possible suitors. <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> declined to say whether the company might raise its offer. He would only say that `` the offer is on the table.'' LIN, which said it was studying the offer, has interests in cellular systems serving <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, in addition to owning seven network-affiliated television stations and a specialty publishing house that produces hardcover tourist guides for hotel rooms. <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON>, LIN's largest shareholder, has franchises serving customers in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>. LIN's rights in five of the nation's top 10 markets `` would fit in very nicely'' with <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON>'s small - to medium-sized properties, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> Details on how the deal would be structured will be announced before the end of the week, <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> said. Analysts estimated <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> has amassed close to $ 3 billion for the acquisition, including $ 1.5 billion through the sale of a 22 percent interest to <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, a $ 1.3 billion line of credit and $ 800 million in cash. A source close to <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> who asked not to be identified confirmed the company had put together around $ 3 billion. <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON>'s offer values LIN at about $ 6.5 billion. But since <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> already owns 9.8 percent of <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION>, it would cost $ 5.85 billion to acquire the remaining shares. Two weeks ago, <ORGANIZATION> LIN </ORGANIZATION> announced its board had approved in principle spinning off a new subsidiary that would own its TV stations. It said it would operate its cellular operations and publishing business as a separate company. LIN said the move was made for operating and strategic reasons and was `` not intended as a precursor to any other corporate transaction.'' <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON>'s cellular telephone systems serve 50 million `` pops,'' an industry measure that refers to market-area population multiplied by percentage ownership in the cellular systems serving those areas. LIN has more than 18 million pops, while <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telesis </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Southwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> each have about 30 million. At $ 6.5 billion, <ORGANIZATION> McCaw </ORGANIZATION> would be paying about $ 360 per pop. As recently as 1986, <PERSON> McCaw </PERSON> was buying franchises for $ 6 per pop.
