<SECOND>BC-UAW-Chronology, Adv 11,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, June 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Significant Dates In UAW History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-UAW</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a summary of major dates in the history of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union, as provided by the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s public information department:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 August 1935 _ <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> charters the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union. Spring 1936 _ <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> bolts from the <ORGANIZATION> AFL </ORGANIZATION> and becomes independent. It later is a co-founder of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organizations </ORGANIZATION>. December 1936 _ <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> begins a sit-down strike at <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> plants in <LOCATION> Flint </LOCATION>. The strike spreads to other <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> plants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. February 1937 _ Workers return to their jobs at <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> plants after a one-page agreement is signed recognizing the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> as the bargaining agent for <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> employees. February 1937 _ <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> ends a 15-week strike with the signing of the first contract with an agricultural implement company, J.I. Case. March 1937 _ A sit-down strike begins at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> plants, ending in union recognition. June 1940 _ <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and the union agree to a contract that includes, for the first time, paid vacations. April 1941 _ The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> strikes <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and gains bargaining-agent recognition. November 1945 _ <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> is struck for 113 days for first postwar pay raise. May 1948 _ The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> agree to the nation's first major cost-of-living protection clause. September 1949 _ <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> agree to the nation's first employer-paid and jointly administered pension fund. February 1950 _ A `` closed shop'' clause is negotiated between the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, making union membership mandatory. May 1950 _ A 104-day strike at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> results in a hospitalization and medical program. April 1954 _ <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> strikes <ORGANIZATION> Kohler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kohler </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, a plumbing products, small engine and generator maker, in what becomes the nation's longest walkout. It's settled five years later. June 1955 _ <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> agree to `` supplemental unemployment benefits,'' the nation's first program to stabilize workers' incomes during layoffs. August 1961 _ <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> sign agreement setting up principle of profit sharing. November 1970 _ After a 10-week strike, <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> agree to the industry's first paid Christmas-New Year's week shutdown. Early 1980s _ <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> agrees to a series of concession contracts with <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> as the automaker flirts with bankruptcy. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is bailed out by federal loan guarantees. Early 1982 _ <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> agrees to concessions contracts at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>. September 1984 _ <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> selectively strikes <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> assembly plants, resulting in job-security gains. An agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> follows a month later. March 1985 _ Most <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> members in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> set up their own union, called the Canadian Auto Workers. Only <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Local 251 in <LOCATION> Wallaceburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, stays with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> union. June 1985 _ <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> and management of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, a joint venture between <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, sign an agreement calling on management cuts before hourly workers are laid off. November 1985 _ <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> completes organizing drives for 22,000 <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> state employees. October 1985 _ <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers approve a contract that brings unionized employees at the Big Three automaker into pay parity. Autumn 1987 _ <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> agrees on new three-year contracts with <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> that strengthens job security language. May 1988 _ <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers approve a contract providing for a signing bonus, improved job security language and an expiration date common with <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, Sept. 14, 1990. June 1988 _ <PERSON> Jai </PERSON> <PERSON> Alai </PERSON> ballplayers in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> choose <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> as their bargaining agent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, June 11</NOTE>
