<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>UAW At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-UAW</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some facts and figures about the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 MEMBERSHIP: About 1 million active and 400,000 retirees in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> now, down from about 1.5 million active and 300,000 retirees in 1979. LOCALS: About 1,200, all in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> except Local 251 in <LOCATION> Wallaceburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>. BARGAINING UNITS: About 3,200. Some locals have more than one bargaining unit. MEMBERSHIP BREAKDOWN: 68 percent in automobile and auto parts industries, 7 percent in the aerospace industry, 6 percent in agricultural implements and about 20 percent in a range of other jobs, including some brewery workers, state employees in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and jai alai players in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. HEADQUARTERS: Solidarity House on the east side of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> along the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. PRESIDENT: <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON>, first elected at 1983 constitutional convention. Faces little challenge for a third term. ORGANIZATION: The union is governed by a 23-member <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> made up of seven officers and 16 regional directors. Every three years, the union holds a constitutional convention, scheduled for June 18-23 this year. HISTORY: Chartered by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> in August 1935, the union grew quickly after a series of sit-down strikes, starting at <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> plants in <LOCATION> Flint </LOCATION>. In ealy 1937, <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> members returned to work after a one-page contract was signed. Workers at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and, later, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> voted to be represented by the union.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Sunday, June 11</NOTE>
