<HEAD>Wheat Price Firm Despite China Turmoil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures opened mixed this morning on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> despite the continued concern over conditions in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Early trading indicates wheat prices are firming, although analysts say traders are worried about delays in the shipment of wheat on order by the Chinese. But the market is largely ignoring the turmoil still evident in that nation and the possible impact it could have on future grain sales. Favorable weather outlooks are expected to put pressure on corn and soybean prices. However, soybean futures could get a boost from a threatened sales boycott by Brazilian farmers who say they are worried about their government's exchange rate policy. In addition, dockworkers in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> are threatening another nationwide port strike, which would hamper that soybean exports. A strike by dockworkers last month shut down most Brazilian ports. In early trading, wheat was a -LCB- cent to 2 cents higher, with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.84 a bushel; corn was -RCB- cent to 1 -LCB- cents lower with July at $ 2.55 -RCB- a bushel; oats were a -LCB- cent to 1 cent higher with July at $ 1.63 a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to 8 cents higher with July at $ 7.19 a bushel. Livestock prices were mostly lower and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .33 cent lower to .23 cent higher with June at 69.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .13 cent higher with August at 78.87 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to .18 cent lower with June at 48.45 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .23 cent to .30 cent higher with July at 32 cents a pound. Livestock and meat futures settled higher Wednesday.
