<HEAD>Time, Warner Weigh Options in Wake of Paramount Bid for Time</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, That bid...with 2 new grafs to UPDATE stock
prices.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communciations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> have an array of options to protect their planned merger deal despite <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 10.7 billion buyout offer for Time. Securities analysts expressed little doubt that Time would resist the unsolicited tender offer that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> launched only 2 -LCB- weeks before shareholders are to vote on the <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> merger that would create the world's largest media and entertainment concern. Top executives of both Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> were said to be unavailable Wednesday for comment on what course they intend to take. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Appert </PERSON>, media analyst at C.J. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grenfell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said he expects Time officials `` will be pretty tough about trying to retain their independence.'' Paramount, the entertainment and publishing concern formerly called <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said late Tuesday it was launching a tender offer of $ 175 in cash for each of Time's shares. That bid prompted heavy trading Wednesday in the stock of all three companies. Time jumped $ 44 to close at $ 170 a share in consolidated <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading, while <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> rose $ 1.75 to $ 53.50 a share and <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> rose 75 cents to $ 54.75 a share. At mid-day today, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> was down $ 2.75 to $ 167.75, <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> was up $ 1.12 -LCB- at $ 54.62 -LCB- and <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> ws up $ 2.12 -LCB- at $ 56.87 -LCB-. Among the options securities analysts said Time was likely to be considering were making its own tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> or turning the tables on Paramount by making a `` Pac-Man'' takeover bid for the uninvited suitor. Analysts said Time previously arranged a $ 5 billion line of credit that could be used if a competing bidder emerged. The down side is that a buyout would dilute Time's earnings by saddling it with debt. They said Time could exercise of any of several takeover defenses, including a `` poison-pill'' that would make stock available to its shareholders at a bargain rate, making a hostile takeover more expensive. Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> also could buy stakes in each other under terms of their merger plan, a move that would further dilute their stock and make a takeover of either of them more costly. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Reidy </PERSON>, media analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said he does n't think the Paramount offer necessarily dooms the <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> merger plan. But he said it is `` hard to envisage a shareholder vote taking place in two weeks while the Paramount offer is outstanding.'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> shareholders are scheduled to vote June 23 on the merger. Paramount filed a lawsuit in <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> seeking to block Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> from exercising contingency plans designed to deter uninvited biddders from interfering with their merger. But a judge declined Wednesday to immediately grant <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s requests. Also Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said it had filed suit in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> against <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>, seeking an order that would prevent the bank from providing or arranging the $ 14 billion in financing that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> said the bank plans to arrange for its bid. The sum includes the cost of buying Time's shares, refinancing debt and other costs. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said it had an agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> under which the bank had agreed not to help finance an unsolicted offer that would interfere with the merger between <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> and Time. In a statement, <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>'s parent, <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION>, said it was not aware of `` any violation of any agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>.'' Paramount Chairman <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> met privately with securities analysts Wednesday, saying that while the deal would result in `` significantly lower'' earnings in the near term, the chance to buy <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> was `` a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to maximize <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION>'s long-term potential.'' He told the analysts he has no plans to sell any assets. Time, a publishing and cable giant, may have a tough job explaining to its shareholders how the proposed stock swap merger with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> would be a better deal than the $ 175 a share in cash that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> is offering. Under the planned <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> merger, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> shareholders would get a share in the new company for each share they currently own while <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> shareholders would get 0.465 share of the new company for each <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> share. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kendrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Noble </PERSON>, media analyst for <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said he estimated the combined company's stock would trade at about $ 110 a share. But he said that figure is not strictly comparable with the $ 175 a share price Paramount is offering, because anyone taking that offer would face a capital gains tax and would have to give up their stock to boot. `` Some credit has to be give to the idea of continuing to be an equity investor,'' he said.
