<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal regulators took over two more savings institutions Thursday _ one in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and another in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> _ bringing the total under government control to 221 in 32 states. The two institutions are <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Portsmouth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, with $ 101 million in assets, and <ORGANIZATION> Horizon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Southampton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, with $ 2.5 billion in assets. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, at President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s direction, has been taking over some insolvent S & amp; Ls since early February The goal is to minimize losses until <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> provides the money to close them or to subsidize their sale to new owners. The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> plans to take over about 60 more institutions in the next several weeks, officials have indicated.
