<FIRST>u f AM-BusinessInvestment Bjt   06-08 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Investment, Bjt,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spending to Expand Business Production Seen Rising</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American businesses plan a strong 6.5 percent increase in plant and equipment spending this year, the government said Thursday, and economists said the investments would help economic expansion while tending to limit inflation. Analysts said much of the spending will involve equipment that would permit businesses to modernize their production capabilities, thereby reducing both costs and prices. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> survey, completed in May, business investment is now estimated at $ 451.43 billion for 1989, up from $ 423.69 billion in 1988. The numbers are adjusted for inflation. Although the economy has been slowing this year, business spending plans have been expanding. In an initial survey completed last December, businesses told the department they planned a 5.9 percent increase in expansion and modernization spending this year. A survey completed in March showed the forecast rising to 6.3 percent. `` Just about all of the increase is projected in equipment rather than physical plants,'' according to <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` This is good, in the sense that it shows that industry is aware that it has to improve product quality and reduce input costs,'' he said. `` To the extent that industry is more productive, it will hold down inflation.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> has been putting upward pressure on interest rates for 15 months as it attempted to slow the economy and ease inflation. The spending forecast suggests the slowdown is not about to turn into recession. `` Basically this is a plus for the economy both in terms of continued expansion and, over the longer time, helping relieve pressure on capacity and therefore limit the extent that price pressures will accelerate,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Aubrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Both <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON> said one drawback to the increased spending is that much of the new equipment is expected to be imported. `` So even as businesses become even more productive on the one side,'' <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON> said, `` on the other, they're adding to the balance of trade deficit.'' But at the same time, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said, much of the spending to increase capacity is to meet expanding orders for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports. Capital spending grew 10.1 percent in 1988 as companies rushed to expand production to meet rising export demand. That was the sharpest increase since a 16.6 percent hike in 1984, when businesses were still recovering from the 1981-82 recession. Since then, spending fell 3.9 percent in 1986 but rose 2.3 percent in 1987. Business investment in the manufacturing sector was forecast to increase 3.6 percent to $ 170.54 billion this year, compared to a 12.8 percent rise in 1988 That includes a 1.4 percent hike in industries producing durable goods, those expected to last three years or more. Non-durable spending was expected to rise 5.7 percent. Non-manufacturing spending in such industries as mining and transportation was seen rising 8.4 percent to $ 280.89 billion, compared with last year's 8.4 percent increase. Before adjusting for inflation, 1989 plant and equipment spending is expected to rise by 9.9 percent to $ 472.08 billion, down from 10.3 percent in 1988.
</TEXT>
