<FIRST>s f BC-UAW Adv11   06-08 1200</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-UAW, Adv 11,1239</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, June 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Autoworkers Union Facing Challenges, Internal Dissent As Convention
Looms</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT5 of June 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to restore advance slugline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Born in protest 54 years ago, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union today advocates constructive teamwork with company bosses and it bargains contracts for professionals who range from clerks to jai alai ballplayers. The 1 million member union is discovering, as have manufacturers and other labor organizations, that peaceful coexistence and diversification can be keys to survival. The transition has come at a price. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> is taking an increasingly active role in running companies, from the board room to the factory floor. This has shaken the workings of a labor organization that up to now has largely avoided the factionalism plaguing some sister unions. As <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> members prepare for a convention later this month, their agenda will include how to address a growing dissident movement that claims the union has forgotten the lessons of history. During the past three years, the New Directions movement has grown within the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> urging the organization's leaders to honor the axiom _ managers manage and workers work. New Directions leader <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> says the union is getting too chummy with management in developing team approaches to the job and assisting with problem-solving on the plant floor. It goes deeper than that, he says. `` I've been trying to force a debate on fundamentals from the start of this thing'' about five years ago, <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> says. `` I'm relentless in my pursuit of answers to why certain hallowed principles have to be discarded And if they have to be discarded in favor of corporatist activity, what's in it for us?'' Jobs, says <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON>. As times change, so must the union. That does n't mean the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> is n't prepared to fight companies. It's been building up a strike fund, which now totals $ 740 million and pays $ 100 a week and insurance coverage per worker during walkout `` They came up with the slogan of New Directions,'' he says. `` I must say that I fail to see that. I sort of equate them to <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> _ I do n't know what that program is because nobody's explained that program.'' The drive of New Directions really is n't new at all, says <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>, director of the Office for the Study of <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> at the University of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. `` New Directions, despite their name, is very much oriented to the old ways,'' he says. The loosely knit group claims widespread shop-level support but declines to estimate it in numbers. In one sense, labor specialists agree, the union will benefit from the debate New Directions is forcing. The movement is by far the most serious and most public challenge to the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> leadership since the union's founding in <LOCATION> Flint </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, on Aug. 26, 1935. `` It's good for the union to have a debate,'' says <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bensman </PERSON>, director of the graduate program in labor studies at <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> `` When you have people who are critical, it forces or gives the leadership more incentive to explain its policies to the members.'' That debate comes as the union looks outside the automobile industry for membership growth. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> has organized some state workers in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, university staff in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <PERSON> jai </PERSON> <PERSON> alai </PERSON> players in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. For years, it has represented aerospace, agricultural equipment and clerical workers. <PERSON> Riki </PERSON> <PERSON> Lasa </PERSON>, a professional <PERSON> jai </PERSON> <PERSON> alai </PERSON> player and president of <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Local 8868, said his organization talked with other unions, including the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> and the Hotel and Restaurant Employees, before deciding in June 1988 to affiliate with the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>. `` They spoke about the democracy within the union that we, the players, make our decisions,'' <PERSON> Lasa </PERSON> says. The 500 players are continuing a strike that began April 14, 1988 over claims that management violated federal labor laws. The jai alai players are seeking their first contract with management. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> also has been looking outside the auto industry in advertising campaigns that have cost the union $ 20 million during the 1980s. The most recent campaign, running in large media markets and costing the union about $ 4 million, reminds Americans of labor's role in building the economy and criticizes financiers to make quick profits on takeovers Some doubt the ad's effectiveness. `` They probably make the people who run them feel better,'' says ad analyst <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Dougherty </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s outside recruiting success has n't been matched in the newest segment of the auto industry _ `` transplants'' from abroad. Japanese companies, and joint ventures between Japanese and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers, have been erecting carmaking plants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> since 1982. Some now are expanding. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> has organized workers at the <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> plant in <LOCATION> Flat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, and two joint ventures _ the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> factory by <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler-Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Diamond-Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> plant in <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, Ill But workers in <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Georgetown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Marysville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Smyrna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, assembly plants are n't unionized `` Nobody will admit this,'' <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> says, `` but there ca n't be any secret as to why they located any of these plants out there in the hinterlands. It's also no accident that most of the people who got hired probably had their ancestry checked through at least three generations to find out whether anyone ever belonged to a union or not. `` We've had an extremely tough time in organizing, and <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> was a good example,'' he said. In March 1986 in <LOCATION> Marysville </LOCATION>, on the eve of a representation election, the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> _ fearing defeat _ withdrew its bid to unionize the workers. <PERSON> Harley </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaiken </PERSON>, a labor professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, says worker boredom could help bring more transplants into the union fold. `` I think they will be organized, I think when they will be organized is hard to gauge,'' he says. In the late 1970s, the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> had more than 1.5 million members. Today, it stands at 1 million, a decline that is a trend in organized labor. Union workers also have become more conservative, partly because of the popularity of former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had a tremendous hold on our membership,'' said former <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON>, now a professor at <ORGANIZATION> Wayne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. `` He was kind of a macho man and the blue-collar worker is sort of a macho fellow and that had a great attraction for them. `` Also I think that some of our members thought that the union leadership and the liberals were too caught up in equal rights, and the other factor is that I believe that as their income increases their values change.'' The base hourly wage for an auto assembler is about $ 14.50 an hour, among the highest of any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> factory worker today. When health and other benefits are included, annual compensation is about $ 37,000, more with overtime. Of that, workers pay the equivalent of two hours pay per month in dues.
</TEXT>
