<HEAD>Kuwait Says It Won't Abide By OPEC Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> said Thursday it will pump extra crude in the coming months in defiance of the latest <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production accord, and other cartel members could follow suit. Just a day after an agreement was reached, Kuwaiti Oil Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalifa </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Sabah </PERSON> said his country has temporarily withdrawn from <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s quota system because other ministers failed to increase its share of total production in the last half of the year. Other members of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries appeared to accept <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s decision to cheat on the new agreement. In fact, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> and a few others were considered likely to ignore their output limits. They, too, wanted a bigger share of the production pie. But <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Boussena </PERSON> said, `` I think that all countries have committed themselves to something. That's what's positive.'' It was <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s insistence on a higher share of increased production that stalled negotiations for a new accord. <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> said he wrote in the new agreement that he would not feel bound by his new quota. But he also told reporters that <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> `` will use that freedom -LRB- from the quota system -RRB- very, very responsibly.'' In restraining supply in the past, he said, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> has `` sacrificed more than the others for a very, very long time. ... But there is a limit to what we can do.'' <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> intended to produce 1.35 million barrels a day in the coming months, noting that it is `` almost physically impossible'' to pump less than that in part because of commitments to long-time customers. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s new new quota is 1.09 million barrels, and its current supply is estimated at nearly 2 million barrels. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Hisham </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON> indicated to a small group of reporters that <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s extra sales would be tolerated as long as they did not exceed 1.35 million barrels a day. <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Ginandjar </PERSON> <PERSON> Kartasasmita </PERSON> noted <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> would have to make cutbacks to come down to the promised level. `` The accord is even better than what we could have dreamed of,'' he said. `` This is the maximum that we could have.'' After six days of bargaining, the cartel agreed to boost its supply ceiling to 19.5 million barrels a day in the July-December period. While that is up a million barrels from the current official level, analysts estimated output in recent weeks has risen to 21 million barrels a day. The ministers agreed to divide the extra sales proportionately among all members. To meet the new ceiling, some countries will have to cut production. <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON> said he would have liked to see the ceiling upped to 20 million barrels a day in the last half of the year, but he noted that `` several of the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members were just afraid it may have an impact on price.'' The ministers said in a statement the ceiling could be raised to 20 million barrels a day or more, effective Oct. 1, if demand remained strong. `` I honestly feel that demand in the market is much stronger,'' <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Boussena </PERSON> agreed, saying that if prices hold steady, `` there is no reason not to add another 500,000 barrels a day'' to the cap. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> retained in the new agreement its benchmark price of $ 18 a barrel. The average price of a basket of seven crudes monitored by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> was nearly $ 17.70 a barrel last week. The new accord was designed to keep a firm grip on production so that prices would remain robust. But oil markets reacted skeptically to the cartel's ability to limit output. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude prices initially tumbled but recovered somewhat on Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members are: <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuella </LOCATION>.
