<HEAD>China Turmoil Damages Foreign Business Confidence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign businesses' confidence in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has been shattered by the eruption of violence. `` It will take years to restore credibility,'' <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> VanDenBerg </PERSON>, an economist at <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States-China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that commercial and economic relations between the countries `` have been disrupted and could suffer long-term damage.'' The business council said its members `` deplore the violent suppression and wanton killing of pro-democracy demonstrators in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'' and said the countries should `` preserve the links between us until they can again be expanded.'' While some businesses away from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> continue to do business as normal, many report they have been crippled by workers staying home and expatriates leaving the country. Many companies that had been attracted by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s cheap labor and huge potential market have been forced into a wait-and-see attitude, hoping their investments will survive. <ORGANIZATION> Kumigai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gumi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a major Japanese construction company, has stopped work on a 51-story skyscraper in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> because of the danger. `` We do n't know when we can resume the project,'' an official said. `` It does n't look like it's going to be any time soon.'' But <ORGANIZATION> Mattel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said it is continuing to operate two toy plants in <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION>, 1,500 miles from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, which make clothes for Barbie dolls and some Disney-theme pre-school toys. <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> ordered 51 employees and dependents at an airliner assembly plant outside <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> to leave the country Tuesday, said <PERSON> Garth </PERSON> <PERSON> Chang </PERSON>, <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' top Asia-based executive in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. Workers were n't aware of the turmoil that had engulfed the country because of the government's news blackout, <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mac </PERSON> <PERSON> Jeffery </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, said the company has 120 employees in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> supplying and maintaining computers. Half are foreigners, he said, and all but two of those had left <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> by Thursday. `` The office is technically open, but if someone needs service, it would depend on the situation whether we could help,'' he said. `` I wonder what business is to be had,'' <PERSON> Jeffery </PERSON> added. About 30 American staffers of an <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> coal mine in north-central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> were on a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government-chartered evacuation flight from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Thursday. They declined to give their names to a reporter at <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> airport, but said there had not been any trouble at the mine. The danger of being on <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> streets caused <ORGANIZATION> Sanyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to tell some 100 workers to remain at home and not report to their jobs at a joint venture plant in the capital making electronic calculators, <ORGANIZATION> Sanyo </ORGANIZATION> said in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Takeshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Itagaki </PERSON> said the company had no problems at a project giving technical assistance to a steel plant near <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, and its exports of steel products to 10 Chinese cities were going ahead normally. <ORGANIZATION> Yokogawa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a leading Japanese manufacturer of industrial instruments, shut a joint venture factory in <LOCATION> Xian </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Shaaxi </LOCATION> province, early this week, said spokesman <PERSON> Takeshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mizuno </PERSON>. The 260 workers `` are participating in rallies in protest against the military suppression in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Mizuno </PERSON> said. `` Even students and workers from other factories are coming to call for a series of major protest rallies. ... Some circles in the city are calling for a general strike.'' Japanese Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hiroshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitsuzuka </PERSON>, speaking in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> Thursday, said, `` It can not be denied that the international image of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has been impaired a lot.'' <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, where for five years the government has urged businessmen to boost trade ties with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, also expressed worry that the violence could damage <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s `` open door'' economic policy of welcoming foreign investment. After hearing of the violence early this week, Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON> said, `` We hope wiser counsels will prevail to pursue conciliation, so that the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people can resume the progress which the open door policies have brought them.'' The turmoil has caused some price jumps for commodities exported by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, such as peanuts, soybeans and silk cocoons.
