<SECOND>AM-China-Singapore Business,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Singapore Firms Brace For China Business Upheaval</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They do n't recognize each other diplomatically, but the world's largest developing country and one of the smallest and most prosperous had been seeking mutual benefits from investment and tourism. Now, bankers and businessmen in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> who followed official calls to try to exploit the vast market in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> are bracing for serious disruption and possible losses. Over the last five years, the government urged businessmen to bolster their established trade ties with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> through direct investments in manufacturing and hotel concerns. In addition, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> lifted travel restrictions on its citizens visiting <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> after a process of gradual easing that began in the early 1980s. The drive to strengthen business ties coincided with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s appointment in 1985 of <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> <PERSON> Keng </PERSON> <PERSON> Swee </PERSON> as an adviser to help develop coastal economic zones <PERSON> Goh </PERSON> is <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s former deputy prime minister and is widely credited with the country's industrial transformation in the 1970s. Hopes of exploiting <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s open-door economic policy are stalled and almost certainly will be reassessed after the turmoil in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` A <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> with large sections of her people, including her best educated, at odds with the government means trouble with people resentful, reforms stalled and economy stagnant,'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON> said after hearing of the initial violence. `` Because of her size, such a <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> could create problems for herself and her neighbors in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> is a small island nation more than 1,000 miles south of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` We hope wiser counsels will prevail to pursue conciliation, so that the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people can resume the progress which the open door policies have brought them,'' the prime minister said. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hsien </PERSON> <PERSON> Loong </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s trade and industry minister and the prime minister's eldest son, offered his country two years ago as an efficient go-between for international traders seeking contacts in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` We can smooth the way for the international business community to do business with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and we can also help, albeit in a small way, to further modernize <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economy.'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hsien </PERSON> <PERSON> Loong </PERSON> said this thriving country was a useful commercial gateway because of formal agreements already in place. These promise to protect investments by the Singapore-based subsidiaries of multinationals, avoid double taxation and guarantee the entry of goods and services into the Chinese market. Tourism officials in 1987 started promoting <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as a complementary destination to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. One objective was to persuade <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> travel agents to arrange package tours featuring <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as joint destinations with common attractions. The <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> connection goes back to <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>'s founding as as British colonial trading post in 1819, when it became a magnet for migrating Chinese peasants. The population is 2.6 million, about 76 percent of whom are ethnic Chinese, and Mandarin is one of four official languages. Despite being only slightly larger than <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s fifth largest export market after <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, much of it for re-export to the rest of southeast <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Trade between <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> quardrupled in the past decade to $ 2.25 billion last year. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> has advised all Singaporeans to leave <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> advised businessmen to postpone trips to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. After the Feb. 23 announcement that <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> would restore diplomatic ties within a year, officials said <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> would follow suit within a few months. Officials declined to comment on whether the turmoil would delay that.
