<HEAD>For Release Sunday, June 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Martin Sorrell: Marketing Maven Builds Ad Empire Through Takeovers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> engineered an industry record $ 566 million purchase of the parent of the <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> advertising agency two summers ago, he called it the `` opportunity of a lifetime.'' But opportunity seems to have knocked more often than the bespectacled 44-year-old financial maven foresaw. His <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> verges on a larger takeover, the $ 864 million buyout of another <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> icon, <ORGANIZATION> Ogilvy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. In his three years at <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> - and Harvard-educated son of a British retailing executive has built a global communications empire He's done it by adding more than three dozen advertising, public relations and marketing services firms to the framework of a company that still makes wire shopping baskets and plastic dish drainers. The Ogilvy deal, expected to close within weeks, will make <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION> the world's second biggest advertising and marketing company, trailing only <ORGANIZATION> Saatchi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Saatchi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> where <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> toiled nine years as the top financial officer <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> has said the <ORGANIZATION> Ogilvy </ORGANIZATION> purchase will make his company the world's finest advertising and marketing services company, but eschews any interest in surpassing <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON> as the largest. His rapid rise to the top of the advertising-marketing industry has left some people gushing at what they call his business genius and others describing him as arrogant and vindictive. <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> has been embroiled in a bitter legal battle for more than a year with a half dozen former executives of the ad agency Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> <PERSON> Federico </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> that <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION> acquired as part of the <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> deal. The Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> executives, including agency founders <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>, walked out in March 1988 to form their own agency after chafing under eight months of <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION> ownership. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Geier </PERSON>, chairman of the advertising conglomerate <ORGANIZATION> Interpublic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>, has criticized <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> for his unsolicited advances against both <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ogilvy </PERSON>. He said <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION>'s assault on <PERSON> Ogilvy </PERSON> exposed <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> as a financial gambler who has `` taken a major company that was doing fine and leveraged it to the hilt.'' <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION> is using a combination of stock and debt to finance the <LOCATION> Ogilvy </LOCATION> takeover. People close to <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> say <PERSON> Geier </PERSON> may be biased since <ORGANIZATION> Interpublic </ORGANIZATION> failed in its eleventh-hour bid to wrest Ogilvy from <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION>'s grasp by proposing a stock swap. Several top executives of the packaging, design, sales promotion and corporate identity firms that <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION> has acquired say they are delighted with the deals. They speak glowingly of the opportunities <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> created for their businesses by associating them with a prestigious name like <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> and by imposing financial discipline they individually lacked. <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION>'s acquisition `` was the best thing that ever happened to <PERSON> Reese </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Pounian </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Reese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a 20-year-old marketing concern based in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION> In a manner typical of <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON>'s approach in acquiring privately held companies, <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> bought <PERSON> Reese </PERSON> in September 1987 for an initial payment of $ 14 million in cash and a promise to pay up to $ 21 million more depending on earnings performance over the next several years. The approach, which <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> honed during his days at <LOCATION> Saatchi </LOCATION>, enables <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION> to hold onto the management of the companies it acquires by giving them a continuing stake in the success of the firm. <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> stays out of the day-to-day operations of <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION>'s companies, but has them file daily financial reports and holds them accountable for meeting performance goals `` The critical thing is what questions you ask,'' <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> said in an interview following the <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> acquisition in 1987. `` If you ask certain things, people in giving you the answers will ask themselves, ` Why did they ask me that question?' Good things come out of that if you are asking the right questions.'' <PERSON> Reese </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Pounian </PERSON> said officials at her company rarely had time to ask themselves the financial questions <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> asks, and she welcomes the discipline. `` Is it a picnic in the park every day? No. ... But the benefits so outweigh the minor inconveniences that there is no question we are in a better position than we would have been,'' she said. <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON>, who pronounces his name with the accent on the first syllable, was born on Valentine's Day in 1945. His father ran the retail division of a large British industrial concern, and the youngster worked in its credit department when he was 16. He studied economics at <ORGANIZATION> Cambridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and earned an MBA from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>. One <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> classmate, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> real estate developer <PERSON> Still </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, remembers <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> as `` very incisive ... very bright'' and a standout in finance. `` If he believed in something, he would persist,'' <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> recalls. After <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> worked for <ORGANIZATION> Glendinning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, a marketing consulting firm in <LOCATION> Westport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>. Later bosses included sports promoter <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormack </PERSON> and food retailer and investor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Gulliver </PERSON>, both in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> It was while working for <PERSON> Gulliver </PERSON> that he met the <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON> brothers. They hired <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> as their top financial officer in 1977 and the firm grew rapidly in the following nine years. <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> struck out on his own in 1986 as chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> Wire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Plastic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION>, precursor of <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. He lives in <LOCATION> Hampstead </LOCATION>, near the north <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> neighborhood where he grew up. He and his wife have three sons, and <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> spends his free time with them, sometimes skiing or playing cricket.
