<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal bankruptcy judge Thursday stripped <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s management of its exclusive right to file a plan to bring the company out of Chapter 11 protection. Judge <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosetti </PERSON>'s action means any creditor can file a plan to compete with one filed by the company's management. Reasons for the decision were not given, but the move came after the about 10 days after <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> filed its fifth plan since entering Chapter 11 in February 1988. Its unsecured creditors are owed $ 220 million. <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>'s lenders and unsecured creditors immediately said they would file reorganization plans of their own. <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>'s most recent plan was to bring its <ORGANIZATION> Sunbeam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, the profitable small appliance maker that includes virtually all of <PERSON> Allegheny </PERSON>'s operating companies, out of Chapter 11 bankruptcy separately from the parent company. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Blum </PERSON>, an attorney representing company stockholders, said <PERSON> Cosetti </PERSON>'s action `` just made getting the financing impossible'' for the <ORGANIZATION> Sunbeam </ORGANIZATION> plan. The last reorganization plan for <ORGANIZATION> Sunbeam </ORGANIZATION> would have paid cash to settle all of the approximately $ 240 million in claims pending against the subsidiary. It would have left the Pittsburgh-based parent still in bankruptcy court to haggle with creditors. After collapse of the fourth reorganization plan, <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said the judge was so aggravated that he suspended payment of most fees to attorneys and accountants involved in the case.
