day higher than the current level but below the estimated daily output in recent weeks of about 21 million barrels. The <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers also decided during their <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> meeting to divide the extra production proportionately among all members. Analysts said this means that some countries will have to curtail some pumping to keep within their self-imposed quotas. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and several other <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members have indicated they intend to pump more crude than their quotas allow and energy brokers doubt <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> will be able to control production enough to maintain strong prices.
