<FIRST>s f BC-SEC-Glance Adv11   06-08 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SEC-Glance, Adv 11,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>Advance for release Sunday, June 11</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-SEC Future</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some facts and figures about the Securities and Exchange Commission:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 HISTORY: The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> was created in 1934 as part of the Securities Exchange Act in a wave of financial regulation under President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> reacting to the stock market crash of 1929 and subsequent Depression. DUTIES: The Washington-based commission is charged with regulating the nation's financial markets and market professionals, including all stock exchanges, brokers and investment firms. It regulates financial disclosures by companies and enforces federal securities laws. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> is run by a panel of five commissioners, including a chairman. It has a total staff of about 2,130, including 800 attorneys, in 13 cities: <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The commission has the power to penalize securities-law violators with fines, suspensions and oversight. It can refer cases to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for criminal prosecution. In 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> brought 252 enforcement actions, including insider trading, corporate reporting, market manipulation, fraud and other cases. It also reviewed 10,985 disclosure filings, 4,000 more than in 1983. FINANCING: The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> had a budget of $ 142.6 million, up from $ 73 million in 1980 It has requested $ 168.7 million for fiscal 1990. In 1987, the commission raised about $ 264 million from stock registration fees and $ 121 million from court orders to defendants to return illicit profits. Under federal securities laws, though, the agency can not use any of the money it raises.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance for Sunday, June 11</NOTE>
