<HEAD>Grain Prices Continue to Tumble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices declined Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> due to continued pressure from favorable weather forecasts and slack demand. On other markets, copper prices were up while precious metals were down; energy prices rallied; livestock and meat futures were down, and sugar and cotton prices rose. Wheat futures, which have been declining because of the political turmoil in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, were off for the third consecutive trading session. Analysts say the problems in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> may mean that country wo n't place new orders for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat. `` There was some concern over <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and additional wheat sales, but the market lacked any real direction,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Kouba </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said Thursday. Soybean futures were mixed, getting a boost from a threatened sales boycott by Brazilian farmers who say they are worried about their government's exchange rate policy. In addition, dockworkers in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> are threatening another nationwide port strike, which would hamper Brazilian soybean exports. Corn prices were pressured by light demand and reports of improved growing conditions in major crop areas. Wheat settled \ cent to 1 -LCB- cents lower with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.81 -RCB- a bushel; corn was 3 cents to 5 cents lower with July at $ 2.53 \ a bushel; oats were 1 -LCB- cents to 2 -LCB- cents higher with July at $ 1.65 a bushel; soybeans were 5 -RCB- cents lower to 3 cents higher with July at $ 7.14 a bushel Copper futures moved higher on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on speculation about supply disruptions. The start of contract talks next week between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producers and their unions, with the possibility of strikes, and the continued closure of <ORGANIZATION> Bougainville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Copper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>'s Papua, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> mine boosted prices, said <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Raptopoulos </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Copper settled 1.10 cents to 2.50 cents higher with June at $ 1.35 a pound. Precious metals prices declined as the dollar showed renewed strength. Gold settled $ 2.60 to $ 3.10 lower with June at $ 373.50 a troy ounce; silver was 2.1 cents to 2.7 cents lower with June at $ 5.443 a troy ounce. Energy futures mostly were higher on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in reaction to promises by <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> to cut back oil production. Kuwaiti Oil Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalifa </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Sabah </PERSON> said his country intended to produce 1.35 million barrels a day in coming months. On Wednesday the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> signed a new production accord that placed <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s new quota at 1.093 million barrels. Its current output is estimated at nearly 2 million barrels a day. West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 12 cents to 33 cents higher with July at $ 20 a barrel; heating oil was .19 cent lower to .17 cent higher with July at 48.66 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .57 cent to .66 cent higher with July at 64 cents a gallon. Livestock and meat futures were mixed in lackluster trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle settled .30 cent lower to .50 cent higher with June at 69.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .15 cent higher with August at 79.02 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent lower to .15 cent higher with June at 48.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .10 cent lower to .52 cent higher with July at 32.25 cents a pound. Sugar futures were up strongly on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The political tension in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which spurred selling earlier in the week, was set aside as rumors spread that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> might enter the market, said <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Badenhop </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> had been expected to enter the market for 300,000 metric tons of sugar. Rumors are that <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> will buy 500,000 metric tons, <PERSON> Badenhop </PERSON> said. Sugar settled .22 cent to .39 cent higher with July at 11.72 cents a pound. Cotton futures continued their run up on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> as new buyers entered the market, said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitten </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Balfour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maclaine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` What spurred the buying was the overselling in reaction to the situation in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Whitten </PERSON> said. `` Equilibrium has been recovered.'' Cotton settled .37 cent to 1.02 cents higher with July at 64.18 cents a pound.
