<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> presented a contract proposal Thursday to the striking pilots union that seeks temporary pay and vacation reductions similar to those implemented for non-union workers last week. The proposal was made at the second official negotiating session since Eastern was hit by a crippling strike March 4. The concessions are necessary to help the airline emerge from bankruptcy, the company said at a news conference. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> responded by describing the news conference as a `` public relations hoax'' and said the contract proposal `` does not address the primary issues'' that led to the strike. Eastern officials said part of the latest proposal is identical to an offer first made last July. New elements include the company's request that pilots take a 10 percent pay cut for six months and a 5 percent cut during the second six months After a year, pay would be fully restored. Eastern also proposed suspending contributions to a pension fund through 1990 and canceling vacations for the rest of this year. As part of its plan to emerge from bankruptcy, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> last week announced an austerity program that includes a 20 percent pay cut for senior management and increased work hours at the same pay for non-union employees. Vacations for those workers have been canceled for the remainder of the year. <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said the union was angry that <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> announced the proposal at a news conference before it was presented to <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> negotiators. `` Obviously the cameras are more important than the contract,'' <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. `` It's nothing more than a public relations hoax presented to establish a paper trail to the doors of the bankruptcy court, where we expect Eastern will file for abrogation of our contract.'' Eastern spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said abrogation of the contract `` is simply an option, one that we would not even address at this time. ... Our primary thrust is to successfully negotiate a pilots' contract. A federal appeals court on Wednesday rejected <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s request to have the pilots ordered back to work. The pilots union says it has been honoring the picket lines of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, while the company argued the pilots were striking to advance their own contract negotiations without going through federal mediation procedures as the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> did. The pilots' last contract expired in July 1988. Negotiations on a new agreement have been held off and on since August 1987. Eastern filed for bankruptcy under Chapter 11 five days after it was crippled by the strike by <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION>, pilots and flight attendants.
