<HEAD>Lawmaker Says Bush Clean Air Plan Promising For Corn Growers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plans to reduce auto emissions are expected to increase demand for corn-based ethanol and expand markets for other corn products, a congressman says. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, said Thursday he expects <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will place greater emphasis on alternative motor fuels, such as ethanol, as part of a clean air program the president is scheduled to announce Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Promotion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has estimated that with just normal growth in gasohol use, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would need 390 million bushels of corn to meet ethanol demand in 1989. About three-quarters of the nation's ethanol is produced in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON> said he expects the president's proposal to increase the demand for gasohol _ a blend of 10 percent ethanol and gasoline _ and to encourage higher concentrations of ethanol _ up to the use of pure ethanol _ as a fuel for cars, buses and trucks. `` If there is a commitment at the national level to have a substantial portion of the automotive fleet in the country, or buses or trucks, being operated by alternative fuels, then there's going to be a major expansion in the use of ethanol,'' <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is a long-time proponent of increasing the use of ethanol to clean auto emissions and reduce carbon monoxide and other pollutants in the air. He promised Thursday that he will unveil `` the most sweeping changes to the Clean Air Act since it was last amended 12 years ago.'' The clean air program also will focus on factory emissions and acid rain. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is scheduled to deliver a speech on alternative fuels at <LOCATION> Lincoln </LOCATION>, Neb. <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON> said he based his assessment on the program's content on discussions he had Wednesday with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chief of staff, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, and other White House officials. `` Our expectation is that the announcement will include substantial incentives for the use of alternative fuels, in some case the requirement for the use of alternative fuels,'' <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON> said. Use of ethanol as a motor fuel is touted for reducing the release into the air of carbon monoxide, nitrogen oxide and smog. <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON> said ethanol also is safer and easier to transport than another alternative fuel, coal-based methanol, because it is not toxic and burns with a visible flame.
