<HEAD>Parent of Seized S&amp;L Sues Federal Regulators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The parent company of <ORGANIZATION> Gibraltar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday sued the federal regulators who now control the thrift, demanding the release of $ 11 million the parent says it is owed. <ORGANIZATION> Gibraltar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s lawsuit, filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, is the latest development in a dispute with federal agencies over whether the holding company will be able to stay afloat now that the thrift is under regulators' control. <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION> Savings, the nation's ninth-largest thrift, with operations in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, was seized March 31 by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which declared the institution unsound. <ORGANIZATION> Gibraltar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION>, a holding company whose stock is publicly traded and which has n't any significant assets other than two <ORGANIZATION> Gibraltar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> units in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, was n't included in the seizure of its thrifts The suit names as defendants the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION>'s own seized subsidiaries. <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyle </PERSON> responded that regulators had ample reason to take over <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION>, and are required by law to preserve the assets of the savings & amp; loan without regard to the fate of the holding company. `` Our responsibility is to the insured deposits and to the depositors and to the <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Hoyle </PERSON> said from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` Unfortunately, that means, in the case of a stock institution, the stockholders, the debtholders, they're cut out.'' The holding company missed a $ 1 million interest payment to bondholders June 1, blaming regulators' withholding of the $ 11 million. <ORGANIZATION> Gibraltar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> has 83 branches and the sister thrift in <LOCATION> Bellevue </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, has six branches in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and 18 in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Together, they had $ 8.8 billion in deposits when seized. <ORGANIZATION> Gibraltar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 100.5 million in 1988 and $ 146.5 million in 1987. In 1986, it had a $ 43.9 million profit.
